es==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|7972336|Cheriyo Doctor}}\n* {{IMDb title|7926170|Cheriyo Captain}}\n* {{IMDb title|7976814|Cheriyo Darling}}\n* {{IMDb title|7971508|Cheriyo Holman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cheriyo}}\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 1991]]\n[[Category:Comedy film series]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan comedy films]]\n", "name_user": "ChinthiSL", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo fixed and wiki pages linked", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cheriyo_(film_series)"}
{"title_page": "Die Hard", "text_new": "{{About|the 1988 action film|the film series it launched|Die Hard (film series)|other uses}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Short description|1988 American action film directed by John McTiernan}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Die Hard\n| image          = Die hard.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[John McTiernan]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lawrence Gordon (producer)|Lawrence Gordon]]\n* [[Joel Silver]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jeb Stuart (writer)|Jeb Stuart]]\n* [[Steven E. de Souza]]\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Nothing Lasts Forever (Thorp novel)|Nothing Lasts Forever]]''|[[Roderick Thorp]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Bruce Willis]]\n* [[Alan Rickman]]\n* [[Alexander Godunov]]\n* [[Bonnie Bedelia]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Michael Kamen]]\n| cinematography = [[Jan de Bont]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Frank J. Urioste]]\n* [[John F. Link]]\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Gordon Company\n* [[Silver Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1988|07|12|Los Angeles|1988|07|15|United States}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes<ref name=\"Runtime\"/>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $28 million<ref name=\"BOMGeneral\"/>\n| gross          = $141.5 million<ref name=\"BOMGeneral\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Die Hard''''' is a 1988 American [[action thriller film]] directed by [[John McTiernan]], written by [[Jeb Stuart (writer)|Jeb Stuart]] and [[Steven E. de Souza]]. Based on [[Roderick Thorp]]'s 1979 novel ''[[Nothing Lasts Forever (Thorp novel)|Nothing Lasts Forever]]'', it was produced by the Gordon Company and [[Silver Pictures]], and distributed by [[20th Century Fox]]. The film follows off-duty [[New York City Police Department]] officer [[John McClane]] ([[Bruce Willis]]) who is caught in a Los Angeles skyscraper on Christmas Eve during a heist led by criminal mastermind [[Hans Gruber (character)|Hans Gruber]] ([[Alan Rickman]]).\n\nMade for $28 million, ''Die Hard'' grossed over $141 million theatrically worldwide. Turning Willis into an action star, the film became a [[metonym]] for an action film in which a lone hero fights overwhelming odds. The film's success spurred creation of the ''[[Die Hard (film series)|Die Hard]]'' franchise, which includes four sequels, a number of video games, and a comic book. In 2017, it was selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]]. ''Die Hard'' has been named one of the [[List of films considered the best#Action|best action]] and [[List of films considered the best#Christmas|Christmas-themed films ever made]].<ref name=\"pajiba\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pajiba.com/guides/the-best-action-films-of-all-time.php | title=Die Hard is #1 according to Pajiba.com | publisher=Pajiba.com | accessdate=November 2, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101174309/http://www.pajiba.com/guides/the-best-action-films-of-all-time.php | archive-date=2011-11-01 | url-status=live | date=2007-05-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN1448232520070615|title=\"Die Hard\" tops magazine list of best action films|work=[[Reuters]]|date=2007-06-15|access-date=2017-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715005610/http://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN1448232520070615|archive-date=2009-07-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/empire-30-greatest-christmas-movies/|title=The 30 Best Christmas Movies Ever|work=Empire|accessdate=8 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006232422/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/empire-30-greatest-christmas-movies/|archive-date=2016-10-06|url-status=live}}</ref> The film also ranks {{Numero|20}} on [[Empire (film magazine)|''Empire'']]{{'}}s 2017 list of the 100 greatest movies of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-movies/|title=The 100 Greatest Movies|website=Empire|access-date=2018-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013202030/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-movies/|archive-date=2018-10-13|url-status=live|date=2018-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- PER WP:FILMPLOT, PLOT SUMMARIES FOR FEATURE FILMS SHOULD BE BETWEEN 400 AND 700 WORDS. -->\nOn Christmas Eve, [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]] detective John McClane arrives in [[Los Angeles]], intending to reconcile with his estranged wife, Holly, at the Christmas party of her employer, the Nakatomi Corporation. McClane is driven to the party by Argyle, a limousine driver. While McClane changes clothes, the party is disrupted by the arrival of a ex-[[West Germany|West German]] radical [[Hans Gruber (character)|Hans Gruber]] and his team: Karl Vreski and his brother Tony, Theo, Franco, Alexander, Marco, Kristoff, Eddie, Uli, Heinrich, Fritz, and James. The group seizes the tower, disables communication to the outside world, and secures those inside as hostages except for McClane, who slips away, and Argyle, who gets stranded in the garage.\n\nGruber interrogates Nakatomi executive Joseph Takagi for the code to the building's vault and reveals that he plans to steal $640 million in [[bearer bond]]s, with the terrorist act merely a distraction. Takagi refuses to cooperate and is killed by Gruber. McClane secretly watches, escapes, and sets off a fire alarm in an attempt to alert authorities. Eddie assures the fire department it is a false alarm. Gruber sends Tony to investigate. McClane kills Tony, pocketing his weapon and radio, which he then uses to alert the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]], who suspect McClane of making a prank call. Sgt. Al Powell is sent to investigate. Gruber sends Heinrich and Marco to stop McClane, who kills them both. Powell arrives, and finding nothing unusual, he prepares to leave, but McClane drops Marco's corpse onto his patrol car to gain his attention. Powell summons the LAPD, who lay siege to the building. McClane steals Heinrich's bag containing [[C-4 (explosive)|C-4 explosives]] and detonators.\n\nJames and Alexander use anti-tank missiles to disable a [[SWAT]] [[M8 Greyhound|armored car]] before McClane drops C-4 attached to an office chair and computer down the elevator shaft, blowing up their floor and killing them. Holly's coworker, Harry Ellis, attempts to mediate between Hans and McClane for the return of the detonators. McClane refuses, prompting Gruber to execute Ellis. While checking explosives attached to the roof, Gruber encounters McClane. Gruber masquerades as an escaped hostage; McClane offers him a gun and Gruber attempts to shoot McClane, but the gun is empty. Karl, Franco, and Fritz arrive; McClane kills Fritz and Franco but is forced to abandon the detonators.\n\nFBI agents take command of the siege, ordering the building's power shut off; this, as Gruber anticipated, disables the vault's final lock. Gruber demands a helicopter on the rooftop for transport to the Los Angeles airport, but the FBI prepare to double-cross him by sending two helicopter gunships. McClane discovers that Gruber intends to detonate the explosives on the roof, faking the deaths of his team so they can escape with the bearer bonds. While making final preparations, Gruber sees a news report by intrusive reporter Richard Thornburg that features McClane's children and deduces from a desk photo that McClane is Holly's husband. The criminals order the hostages to the roof, but Gruber takes Holly with him to use against McClane, who subdues Karl in a fight before heading up to the roof. After killing Uli, he sends the hostages downstairs as the FBI helicopters appear and shoot at McClane, believing him to be a terrorist. Gruber detonates the explosives, destroying the roof and one helicopter; McClane barely survives.\n\nTheo retrieves their getaway vehicle, an ambulance before Argyle rams it with the limo and knocks Theo unconscious. A weary McClane finds Holly with Gruber and his remaining men, Eddie and Kristoff. After knocking Kristoff unconscious, McClane confronts Gruber and is ordered to surrender his submachine gun. McClane does this to spare Holly but distracts Gruber and Eddie by laughing, allowing him to grab a concealed pistol taped to his back that contains two bullets. McClane wounds Gruber and kills Eddie; Gruber crashes through a window but grabs onto Holly's wrist. Gruber makes a last-ditch attempt to kill the pair, but McClane removes Holly's wristwatch, and Gruber falls to his death.\n\nOutside, McClane and Holly meet Powell. Karl emerges and attempts to shoot McClane, but is killed by Powell. Argyle crashes through the parking garage door in the limo. Thornburg arrives and attempts to interview McClane, but Holly punches him before she and McClane leave the area with Argyle.\n\n==Cast==\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = horizontal\n   | footer = Bruce Willis in 2010 (left) and Alan Rickman in 2011; ''Die Hard'' was Rickman's first cinema appearance and Willis's second leading role in a major Hollywood production.\n   | image1 = Bruce Willis by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n   | width1 = 164\n   | image2 = Alan Rickman BAM 2011-01-15 n1.jpg\n   | width2 = 154\n  }}\n* [[Bruce Willis]] as [[John McClane]], a streetwise New York cop who has come to Los Angeles to reconcile with his wife\n* [[Alan Rickman]] as [[Hans Gruber (character)|Hans Gruber]], an extremist recently expelled from a West German political terrorist group and the leader of the terrorists\n* [[Alexander Godunov]] as Karl Vreski, Hans's second-in-command and Tony's brother\n* [[Bonnie Bedelia]] as [[John McClane#Family|Holly Gennero-McClane]], John's estranged wife\n* [[Reginald VelJohnson]] as Sgt. Al Powell\n* [[Paul Gleason]] as Dwayne T. Robinson, the Deputy Chief of Police\n* [[De'voreaux White]] as Argyle, John's limousine driver\n* [[William Atherton]] as Richard Thornburg, an arrogant reporter\n* [[Clarence Gilyard]] as Theo, Hans's tech specialist\n* [[Hart Bochner]] as Harry Ellis, a sleazy Nakatomi executive\n* [[James Shigeta]] as Joseph Yoshinobu Takagi, Nakatomi's head executive\n\nAdditional cast includes Hans's henchmen: Bruno Doyon as Franco, [[Andreas Wisniewski]] as Tony Vreski, Joey Plewa as Alexander, [[Lorenzo Caccialanza]] as Marco, Gerard Bonn as Kristoff, [[Dennis Hayden (actor)|Dennis Hayden]] as Eddie, [[Al Leong]] as Uli, Gary Roberts as Heinrich, Hans Buhringer as Fritz, and [[Wilhelm von Homburg]] as James. [[Robert Davi]] and [[Grand L. Bush]] appear as FBI Special Agent Big Johnson and Agent Little Johnson, respectively, [[Tracy Reiner]] appears as Thornburg's assistant, and [[Taylor Fry]] and Noah Land make minor appearances as McClane's children [[John McClane#Lucy McClane|Lucy McClane]] and [[John McClane#John \"Jack\" McClane Jr.|John Jr.]]\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Foxplaza la.jpg|thumb|right|[[Fox Plaza (Los Angeles)|Fox Plaza]], which served as the setting for Nakatomi Plaza]]\n\nProduced by Lawrence Gordon and Joel Silver, the film is based on [[Roderick Thorp]]'s 1979 novel ''[[Nothing Lasts Forever (Thorp novel)|Nothing Lasts Forever]]'', the sequel to 1966's ''[[The Detective (novel)|The Detective]]''. The latter novel was adapted into a 1968 [[The Detective (1968 film)|film of the same name]] starring [[Frank Sinatra]] and was a box-office success. When a movie based on Thorp's sequel went into production, the studio was contractually obligated to offer Sinatra the lead role in ''Die Hard''.<ref name=Independent1/> Sinatra, then in his early 70s, turned down the project.<ref name=Independent1/> The story was then changed to have no connection to ''The Detective''.<ref name=Independent1/> [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] declined the role as he wished to broaden his appeal by attempting comedy in what eventually became ''[[Twins (1988 film)|Twins]]''. Although it has been rumored that at this point the project was repurposed to be a sequel to Schwarzenegger's 1985 action film ''[[Commando (1985 film)|Commando]]'', scriptwriter de Souza has denied this.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bristolbadfilmclub.co.uk/2015/03/19/exclusive-interview-part-2-steven-e-desouza-writerdirector-of-street-fighter/|title=Exclusive Interview (Part 2): Steven E. DeSouza (writer/director of Street Fighter)|work=Bristol Bad Film Club|access-date=2015-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329123136/http://www.bristolbadfilmclub.co.uk/2015/03/19/exclusive-interview-part-2-steven-e-desouza-writerdirector-of-street-fighter/|archive-date=2015-03-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> De Souza has said he wrote the script as if Hans Gruber were the protagonist. \"If he had not planned the robbery and put it together, Bruce Willis would have just gone to the party and reconciled or not with his wife. You should sometimes think about looking at your movie through the point of view of the villain who is really driving the narrative.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://creativescreenwriting.com/there-is-no-such-thing-as-an-action-movie-steven-e-de-souza-on-screenwriting/|title=\"There is no such thing as an action movie.\" Steven E. de Souza on Screenwriting|last=Frazier|first=Dan|date=August 24, 2015|publisher=Creative Screenwriting|accessdate=August 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915041138/http://creativescreenwriting.com/there-is-no-such-thing-as-an-action-movie-steven-e-de-souza-on-screenwriting/|archive-date=2015-09-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Schwarzenegger, the role was offered to a variety of other actors, including [[Richard Gere]], [[Clint Eastwood]], [[Burt Reynolds]], [[Sylvester Stallone]], [[Harrison Ford]], [[Don Johnson]], [[Nick Nolte]], [[Mel Gibson]] and [[Richard Dean Anderson]], all of whom turned it down.<ref name=\"DevOtherActors\"/><ref name=\"CastReynolds\"/> Fast running out of options, demographic data from [[CinemaScore]] helped persuade the studio, the producers and director [[John McTiernan]] to offer the role to Bruce Willis.<ref name=\"lawrence20160830\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/neon/las-vegan-s-polling-company-keeps-tabs-hollywood |title=Las Vegan's polling company keeps tabs on Hollywood |last=Lawrence |first=Christopher |date=2016-08-30 |newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal |access-date=2016-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224100303/http://www.reviewjournal.com/neon/las-vegan-s-polling-company-keeps-tabs-hollywood |archive-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAt the time, Willis was largely known for his comedic role as detective David Addison on the television series ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'' and also had co-starred in the 1987 comedy film ''[[Blind Date (1987 film)|Blind Date]]'' directed by [[Blake Edwards]]. Willis initially turned down the role due to his contractual commitments to ''Moonlighting''. However, after his co-star [[Cybill Shepherd]] became pregnant, ''Moonlighting'' was shut down for 11 weeks which provided sufficient time for Willis to work on ''Die Hard''.<ref name=Independent1>{{cite news |last= Power |first= Ed  |title= Die Hard at 30: How the every-dude action movie defied expectations and turned Bruce Willis into a star |newspaper= The Independent |date= November 26, 2018 |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/die-hard-at-30-anniversary-bruce-willis-john-mcclane-action-movie-christmas-john-mctiernan-a8642466.html |accessdate= November 27, 2018}}</ref> Willis was paid $5 million to star in the film, a figure virtually unheard of at the time for an actor who had, up to that point in time, starred in only one moderately successful film, and normally only paid to major stars such as [[Dustin Hoffman]] and [[Warren Beatty]]. Then-20th Century Fox president [[Leonard Goldberg]] justified the cost, stating the film was reliant on its lead actor, while other sources within the studio would state that Fox was desperate for a star for ''Die Hard'', intended to be its big summer action blockbuster, especially since they had already been turned down by so many other suitable actors.<ref name=\"DevWillisSalary\"/> As the studio didn't believe in Willis's action star appeal the marketing campaign's initial billboards and posters reflected this, and Willis's face was not a focal point,<ref name=\"DevOtherActors\"/> consistent with CinemaScore's suggestion to emphasize the film's action instead of a star without experience in such films.{{r|lawrence20160830}}\n\nWillis's first day on set was on November 2, 1987, when they shot the nighttime scene of him jumping with a fire hose around his waist as an explosion occurred behind  what appeared to be the top of the Nakatomi tower behind him, following the completion of that day's filming on ''Moonlighting'' at Lorimar Studios (now [[Sony Pictures Studios]]) in [[Culver City, California]].<ref name=Independent1/>, In reality, he jumped from the roof of a five-story parking garage onto an airbag. The force of the explosion blew him out to the very edge of the airbag. When upon completing the stunt Willis inquired why they hadn't filmed such a dangerous scene at the end of production, he was told that if they had, then they would have run the expensive risk of having to reshoot the whole movie with another actor.<ref name=Independent1/>\n\nMcTiernan did not want the villains to be terrorists, considering them too mean. He chose to avoid the terrorists' politics in favor of making them thieves in pursuit of monetary gain, believing it would make the film more suitable for summer entertainment. The film's ending had not been finalized by the time filming had begun; one result is that the truck depicted as transporting the terrorists to the building is too small to house the ambulance that was later revealed to be inside it. Other scenes also lacked context: [[production designer]] Jackson De Govia had built the building's computer room before they knew what it would be used for. Likewise, the character of McClane had not been fully realized until almost halfway through production, when McTiernan and Willis decided that he was a man who did not like himself very much, but was doing the best he could in a bad situation. In the original script, ''Die Hard'' took place over three days, but McTiernan was inspired to have it take place over a single night by Shakespeare's ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]''.<ref name=\"DevMisc\"/>\n\nThe corporate headquarters of [[20th Century Fox]], [[Fox Plaza (Los Angeles)|Fox Plaza]] in [[Century City]] (which had opened a year prior to the film's release), serves as the film's setting for both external and internal scenes. At the time of filming, the building was still under construction, and the setting for a scene of McClane exploring an unfinished floor complete with construction equipment was real\u2014after filming (and construction) was completed, the room used for that scene became the office of former President [[Ronald Reagan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/inside-ronald-reagans-die-hard-635440 |title=Inside Ronald Reagan's Die Hard Office |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=2018-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005190728/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/inside-ronald-reagans-die-hard-635440 |archive-date=2018-10-05 |url-status=live }}</ref> De Govia came up with the idea to use the building. The Nakatomi building's 30th floor, where the hostages are held, was a recreation of the [[Frank Lloyd Wright]]-designed house [[Fallingwater]], including a large rock with water dripping from it. Govia's inspiration came from Japanese corporations of the time buying up American products, his rationale being that Nakatomi had bought Fallingwater and reassembled it in their own building. The building's logo originally was too reminiscent of a [[swastika]] for McTiernan; the final design is closer to a Samurai warrior's helmet. A 380-foot-long [[matte painting]] provided the city backdrop as viewed from inside the Nakatomi building's 30th floor. It featured animated lights and other lighting techniques to present both moving traffic and day and night cycles. {{as of|2011}}, the painting is still in Fox's inventory and is sometimes used in other films. For the film's night exterior shots, cinematographer [[Jan de Bont]] employed a 50mm T1.1 anamorphic lens - the fastest such lens available - and push-processed the film by an additional stop in order to capture the city lights.\n\nThe scene in which the SWAT [[M8 Greyhound|Greyhound armored vehicle]] knocks over a stair railing at the front of Fox Plaza required months of negotiations with Fox to gain approval. The end helicopter scene took six months of preparation, and the production was given only two hours in which to film it. It took three attempts above Fox Plaza, nine camera crews, and no one but crew members was allowed within 500 feet of the line of flight. The scene of McClane falling down a ventilation shaft and catching onto a lower opening was the result of an accident after Willis' stunt man fell. Editor [[Frank J. Urioste]] chose to use the unintentional scene in the final film.<ref name=\"DevMisc\"/>\n\n''Die Hard'' was [[Alan Rickman]]'s first feature film role.<ref name=\"LegacyEmpire\"/> Rickman was cast after producer Joel Silver saw his performance as Vicomte de Valmont in the Broadway run of ''Les Liaisons Dangereuses''.<ref name=Independent1/> For his death scene, he was dropped {{convert|70|ft}} on a [[Chroma key|blue screen]] set. The shot used was the first take; Rickman was dropped sooner than he had been told he would be, so the look of fear on his face is genuine, an act that reportedly angered the actor.<ref name=\"DevMisc\"/> The DVD text commentary track reveals that the shooting script did not originally include the meeting between McClane and Gruber pretending to be a hostage; it was only written in when it was discovered that Rickman could perform a convincing American accent.\n\n==Release==\nThe premiere of ''Die Hard'' took place on July 12, 1988, at the AVCO theater in Los Angeles, California.<ref name=\"Premiere\"/>\n''Die Hard'' had its inaugural British screening at the London Film Festival on 27 November 1988.<ref name=Independent1/>\n\n===Box office===\n''Die Hard'' opened in limited release in 21 theaters on July 15, 1988, earning $601,851\u2014an average of $28,659 per theater. The film began a wide release in North America on July 20, 1988, earning approximately $7.1 million from 1,276 theaters\u2014an average of $5,568 per theater\u2014finishing as the weekend's number three film. By the time ''Die Hard'' ended its theatrical run, it had earned $83 million in North America and a further $57.7 million from markets elsewhere, totaling $140.7 million.<ref name=\"BOMGeneral\"/>\n\n===Home media===\n''Die Hard'' was released on [[DVD-Video|DVD]] on June 19, 2007, a [[Blu-ray]] Disc release followed on November 20, 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/669/Die-Hard.html|title=Die Hard DVD Release Date|website=DVDs Release Dates|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523095357/https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/669/Die-Hard.html|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released on [[4K resolution|4K]] [[Ultra-high-definition television|UHD]] Blu-ray on May 15, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultrahd.highdefdigest.com/56659/diehard4kultrahdblurayfrenchimport.html|title=High Def Digest {{!}} Blu-ray and Games News and Reviews in High Definition|website=ultrahd.highdefdigest.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523095717/https://ultrahd.highdefdigest.com/56659/diehard4kultrahdblurayfrenchimport.html|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n{{expand section|date=February 2018}}\nOn release, ''Die Hard'' drew ambivalent reviews from critics.<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|title=Die Hard (1988)|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/55749|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=February 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211071728/https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/55749|archive-date=2018-02-11|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave it a less-than-flattering review, rating it a mere two stars out of a possible four. Despite considering it well made and performed (particularly Rickman's role) Ebert criticized the stupidity of Gleason's deputy police chief character, claiming that \"all by himself he successfully undermines the last half of the movie.\"<ref>{{cite news |title = Die Hard |url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19880715/REVIEWS/807150301/1023 |publisher = [[Roger Ebert]], [[Chicago Sun-Times]] |accessdate = December 17, 2009 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110302012747/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F19880715%2FREVIEWS%2F807150301%2F1023 |archive-date = 2011-03-02 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nRetrospective reviews have been much more positive. On [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 93% based on 76 reviews, and an average rating of 8.53/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Its many imitators (and sequels) have never come close to matching the taut thrills of the definitive holiday action classic.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\"/> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 70 out of 100, based on 13 critics, which indicates \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"Metacritic\" /> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nordine|first1=Michael|title=Best CinemaScore Ratings: Movies With an 'A+' From the Audience|url=http://www.indiewire.com/gallery/best-cinema-score-rating-movies-a-audience-score/#!10/die-hard-1988-2/|accessdate=December 4, 2017|work=[[indieWire]]|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=November 26, 2017|quote=''Die Hard'' is located page 10 of the article's photo gallery.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204223007/http://www.indiewire.com/gallery/best-cinema-score-rating-movies-a-audience-score/#!10/die-hard-1988-2/|archive-date=2017-12-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Critics' rankings====\nSome critics have ranked the film on respective lists of the all-time best Christmas films (see below, [[Die Hard#Status as a Christmas film|Status as a Christmas film]], for further discussion):\n* [[Digital Spy]] \u2013 #5<ref>{{cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|title=Muppet Christmas Carol tops Digital Spy favourite Christmas film poll|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a356141/muppet-christmas-carol-tops-digital-spy-favourite-christmas-film-poll.html|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|date=December 19, 2011|accessdate=December 24, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108014025/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a356141/muppet-christmas-carol-tops-digital-spy-favourite-christmas-film-poll.html|archive-date=2012-01-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' \u2013 #1<ref>{{Cite news |title=The 30 Best Christmas Movies Ever |url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p29 |work=empireonline.com |publisher=Bauer Consumer Media |date=December 2010 |accessdate=2011-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322165455/http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p29 |archive-date=2012-03-22 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' \u2013 #4<ref>{{cite news|title=20 Top Christmas Movies Ever|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20317203_20449281_20888961,00.html|first=Chris|last=Nashawaty|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=2011-12-26|access-date=2014-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220044906/http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20317203_20449281_20888961,00.html|archive-date=2014-12-20|url-status=live}}<hive-date=2017-11-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Guardian]]'' \u2013 #8<ref>{{cite news|title=Guardian Greatest christmas movies Elf #4|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/nov/29/urite-film-poll-wonderful|publisher=HanMan|access-date=2016-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217143938/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/nov/29/christmas-favourite-film-poll-wonderful|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2011-11-29|last1=Child|first1=Ben}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' \u2013 #4<ref>{{cite news|title=Elf #6 Greatest xmas film of all time|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/best-christmas-movies-grinch-rudolph-395660#4-die-hard|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Aaron|last=Couch|access-date=2014-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206234656/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/best-christmas-movies-grinch-rudolph-395660#4-die-hard|archive-date=2015-02-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[San Francisco Chronicle|San Francisco Gate]]'' \u2013 #1<ref>{{cite news|title=Today's Special: Best Christmas Movies of All Time (Updated!)|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/thebigevent/2011/12/22/todays-special-best-christmas-movies-of-all-time/#photo-34458|work=The San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=2014-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220043810/http://blog.sfgate.com/thebigevent/2011/12/22/todays-special-best-christmas-movies-of-all-time/#photo-34458|archive-date=2014-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe film was nominated for four [[61st Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]: [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Effects Editing]] ([[Stephen Hunter Flick]] and [[Richard Shorr]]), [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound|Best Sound]] ([[Don Bassman|Don J. Bassman]], [[Kevin F. Cleary]], [[Richard Overton (sound engineer)|Richard Overton]] and [[Al Overton Jr.]]) and [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]] ([[Richard Edlund]], [[Al DiSarro]], [[Brent Boates]] and Thaine Morris).<ref name=\"Oscars1989\"/> [[Michael Kamen]]'s score earned him a [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI TV/Film Music Award]] in 1989.<ref name=\"AccoBMI\"/>\n\n==Music==\nThe main theme from the finale of [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]]'s [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|9th Symphony]] (commonly known as \"Ode to Joy\") is featured prominently in [[Michael Kamen]]'s score throughout the film, in many guises and variations (mostly as a [[leitmotif]] for Gruber and the terrorists), and thematic variations on \"[[Singin' in the Rain (song)|Singin' in the Rain]]\" are also featured, as the theme for the character Theo. McTiernan said that he incorporated those themes into the film's soundtrack as an homage to [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[A Clockwork Orange (film)|A Clockwork Orange]]'' (which featured both pieces of music).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amc.com/talk/2008/02/die-hards-debt|title=Die Hard's Debt to A Clockwork Orange and Beethoven|access-date=2017-12-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229233731/http://www.amc.com/talk/2008/02/die-hards-debt|archive-date=2017-12-29|url-status=live}}</ref> Basing his score around thematic variations on well-known pieces is a concept that Kamen previously used in ''[[Brazil (1985 film)|Brazil]]''. [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]'s [[Brandenburg Concertos|''Brandenburg Concerto No. 3'']] is playing during the party sequence near the film's beginning.\n\nAs the film has a Christmas setting, the score also features sleigh bells in some cues, as well as the Christmas pop standard \"[[Winter Wonderland]]\". Two 1987 pop songs are used as source music: near the film's beginning, limousine driver Argyle plays the rap song \"[[Christmas in Hollis]]\", performed by [[Run-DMC]], and, later, while talking on the phone in the limousine, Argyle is listening to [[Stevie Wonder]]'s \"[[Skeletons (Stevie Wonder song)|Skeletons]]\". The end credits of the film begin with the Christmas song \"[[Let It Snow! Let It Snow! Let It Snow!]]\" (performed by [[Vaughn Monroe]]) and continue with Beethoven's 9th Symphony.\n\nThe film's final four minutes were tracked with music from two other Twentieth Century Fox features; these were temporary tracks which the studio decided to leave in the film. The music heard when McClane and Powell see each other for the first time is from [[John Scott (composer)|John Scott]]'s score for the 1987 film ''[[Man on Fire (1987 film)|Man on Fire]]''. When Karl appears with his rifle, McTiernan decided that he did not like Kamen's produced music for the scene and chose to use a piece of temporary score that the production had purchased. The piece was part of the score composed by [[James Horner]] for the 1986 science fiction action film ''[[Aliens (film)|Aliens]]''.<ref name=\"DevMisc\"/>\n\nSimilarly to ''Aliens'', the score by Michael Kamen was heavily edited, with music samples looped over and over and cues added to scenes. The most notable example is the \"brass blast\" heard when John slams the chair at the window as he confronts Marco, then Heinrich appears and he kills him, and later when Hans Gruber falls to his death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/die_hard.html|title=Filmtracks: Die Hard (Michael Kamen)|accessdate=2009-07-10|publisher=Filmtracks.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701235511/http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/die_hard.html|archive-date=2009-07-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe score as heard in the film was released by [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]] in February 2002, but was limited to 3,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.varesesarabande.com/details.asp?pid=VCL%2D0202%2D1004 |title=Die Hard by Michael Kamen |accessdate=2009-07-10 |publisher=Varesesarabande.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016021428/http://www.varesesarabande.com/details.asp?pid=VCL-0202-1004 |archivedate=October 16, 2007 }}</ref> It was subsequently reissued by La-La Land Records in November 2011, in a two-disc limited edition of 3,500 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lalalandrecords.com/Die.html|title=Die Hard by Michael Kamen|accessdate=2014-05-29|website=lalalandrecords.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529085641/http://www.lalalandrecords.com/Die.html|archivedate=2014-05-29}}</ref> In addition to the Kamen score, this release also includes the Monroe and Beethoven end credits pieces, Run-DMC's \"Christmas in Hollis,\" and the John Scott track from ''Man on Fire''.\n\n==Legacy==\nThe film spawned four sequels: ''[[Die Hard 2]]'' (1990), ''[[Die Hard with a Vengeance]]'' (1995), ''[[Live Free or Die Hard]]'' (2007), and ''[[A Good Day to Die Hard]]'' (2013). In July 2007, Bruce Willis donated the undershirt worn in the film to the [[National Museum of American History]] at the [[Smithsonian Institution]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/willis.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120909191903/http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/willis.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 9, 2012 |title=Die Hard Donation |last1=Crawford |first1=Amy |date=July 1, 2007 |publisher=Smithsonian.com |accessdate=September 10, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n''Die Hard'' established what would be a common formula for action films over the next decade, featuring a lone [[everyman]] against a colorful terrorist character in an isolated setting.<ref name=\"guardian 30th\">{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/12/die-hard-30th-anniversary-quintessential-action-movie | title = Die Hard at 30: how it remains the quintessential American action movie | first = Scott | last = Tobias | date = July 12, 2018 | accessdate = July 12, 2018 | work = [[The Guardian]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180712111933/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/12/die-hard-30th-anniversary-quintessential-action-movie | archive-date = 2018-07-12 | url-status = live }}</ref> Several of these films that followed this formula were often referred to as \"''Die Hard'' on a _____\", such as ''[[Under Siege]]'' (1992, \"''Die Hard'' on a battleship\"), ''[[Passenger 57]]'' (1992, \"''Die Hard'' on a plane\") and ''[[Speed (1994 film)|Speed]]'' (1994, \"''Die Hard'' on a bus\").<ref name=\"guardian 30th\"/><ref name = \"Die Hard on a bus\">{{Cite book | last = Weinberger | first = Everett | title = Wannabe: A Would-Be Player's Misadventures in Hollywood | publisher = Macmillan | year = 1997 | page = 52 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=m6IFlodX4E4C&pg=PA52 | isbn = 0-312-15708-8 }}</ref> Such a trend would continue until films like ''[[The Rock (film)|The Rock]]'' (1996, also dubbed \"''Die Hard'' on [[Alcatraz Island|an island]]\") changed the tone and feel of how action movies going forward were made, and which further changed with the evolution of CGI effects exemplified by ''[[The Matrix]]'' (1999).<ref name=\"guardian 30th\"/><ref>''The Movies of the Eighties'' (1990) by Ron Base and David Haslam.</ref> Other 1990s action films featuring the Die Hard scenario include ''[[Cliffhanger (film)|Cliffhanger]]'', ''[[Under Siege 2: Dark Territory]]'', ''[[Sudden Death (1995 film)|Sudden Death]]'', ''[[Broken Arrow (1996 film)|Broken Arrow]]'', ''[[Executive Decision]]'', ''[[Con Air]]'', ''[[Speed 2: Cruise Control]]'', and ''[[Air Force One (film)|Air Force One]]''. Scott Tobias of ''[[The Guardian]]'' observed that none of these following films readily captured the complete effectiveness of the ''Die Hard'' story.<ref name=\"guardian 30th\"/>\n\nIn 2001, ''Die Hard'' was listed at #39 on AFI's ''[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Thrills|100 Years... 100 Thrills]]'', a list of America's most heart-pounding films.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/thrills100.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Thrills |accessdate=2014-06-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328082214/http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/thrills100.pdf |archive-date=2014-03-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2003, Hans Gruber was listed at #46 on ''[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains|the AFI's 100 Years... 100 Heroes and Villains]]'' list.<ref>[http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/handv100.pdf ''AFI'S 100 YEARS...100 HEROES AND VILLAINS''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328082215/http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/handv100.pdf |date=2014-03-28 }} handv100.pdf</ref> It was selected by ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine as #29 on their \"500 Greatest Movies of All Time\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/500/91.asp|title=The 500 Greatest Movies Of All Time|work=Empire|accessdate=January 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310180609/http://www.empireonline.com/500/91.asp|archive-date=2012-03-10|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, the film was selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]] as being \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-17-178/|title=2017 National Film Registry Is More Than a 'Field of Dreams'|date=December 13, 2017|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=December 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213180919/https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-17-178/|archive-date=2017-12-13|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2006, Gruber was listed as the 17th-greatest film character by ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''.<ref name=\"LegacyEmpire\"/> John McClane was placed at number 12 on the same list.<ref>[http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=12 The 100 Greatest Movie Characters| 12. John McClane | Empire] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602093301/http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=12 |date=2013-06-02 }}. empireonline.com (2006-12-05). Retrieved on 2011-01-14.</ref> In the June 22, 2007 issue of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' it was named the best action film of all time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN1448232520070615|title=\"Die Hard\" tops magazine list of best action films|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=June 15, 2007|access-date=2017-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715005610/http://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN1448232520070615|archive-date=2009-07-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Status as a Christmas film===\nIn 2010, ''Die Hard'' was voted as \"The Greatest Christmas Film of All Time\" by ''Empire''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p30|title=The 30 Best Christmas Movies Ever|publisher=Empireonline.com|accessdate=2011-01-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120055157/http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p30|archive-date=2012-01-20|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, [[IGN]] listed it at the top spot on their list of \"The Top 25 Action Movies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/the-top-25-action-movies?page=5|title=The Top 25 Action Movies|website=[[IGN]]|author=<!--Staff writers; no byline.-->|date=2012-01-09|accessdate=2016-12-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221153925/http://www.ign.com/articles/the-top-25-action-movies?page=5|archive-date=2016-12-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Debates have been had about whether or not ''Die Hard'' should be considered a Christmas film. Some feel that because the events of the film occur on Christmas Eve and its setting includes a Christmas party, that is enough to qualify it as a Christmas film, while others feel that since the film is not actually about Christmas and focuses on an action plot involving a lone police officer trying to stop terrorists, it should not be considered a Christmas film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/item/4729e8ae-ca0b-4d4a-a43a-36e29cc33296|title=People are claiming Die Hard is a Christmas film and it's tearing the internet apart|first=Tomasz|last=Frymorgen|date=28 November 2017|website=BBC Three|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224010346/http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/item/4729e8ae-ca0b-4d4a-a43a-36e29cc33296|archive-date=2017-12-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/die-hard-is-the-best-christmas-film-top-films-to-watch-holiday-poll-list-not-a8092761.html|title=Die Hard is officially not a Christmas film|work=The Independent|date=5 December 2017|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224145713/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/die-hard-is-the-best-christmas-film-top-films-to-watch-holiday-poll-list-not-a8092761.html|archive-date=2017-12-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nerdist.com/die-hard-christmas-movie/|title=Does DIE HARD Really Qualify as a Christmas Movie?|publisher=Nerdist|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223030626/https://nerdist.com/die-hard-christmas-movie/|archive-date=2017-12-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/die-hard-christmas-movie-debate-calgary-eyeopener-1.4450305|title=Why Die Hard is the ultimate Christmas movie \u2014 despite naysayers|publisher=CBC|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226162909/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/die-hard-christmas-movie-debate-calgary-eyeopener-1.4450305|archive-date=2017-12-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/tom-ward/why-die-hard-is-the-best-christmas-movie-of-all-time_b_2339117.html|title=Why Die Hard Is the Best Christmas Movie of All Time|work=Huffington Post|date=24 December 2012|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171217014838/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/tom-ward/why-die-hard-is-the-best-christmas-movie-of-all-time_b_2339117.html|archive-date=2017-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1600567/die-hard-home-alone-and-more-of-our-favorite-secret-christmas-movies/|title='Die Hard,' 'Home Alone' And More Of Our Favorite 'Secret' Christmas Movies|publisher=MTV|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014130031/http://www.mtv.com/news/1600567/die-hard-home-alone-and-more-of-our-favorite-secret-christmas-movies/|archive-date=2018-10-14|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 24, 2017, screenwriter [[Steven E. de Souza]] stated on [[Twitter]] that ''Die Hard'' is a Christmas film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/die-hard-christmas-film-bruce-willis-yougov-poll-screenwriter-steven-de-souza-a8127841.html|title=Die Hard screenwriter says it is a Christmas movie: 'A woman about to give birth features prominently'|date=2017-12-25|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225214314/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/die-hard-christmas-film-bruce-willis-yougov-poll-screenwriter-steven-de-souza-a8127841.html|archive-date=2017-12-25|url-status=live}}</ref> However, at his [[Comedy Central Roast]], Willis declared \"''Die Hard'' is not a Christmas movie! It is a goddamn Bruce Willis movie!\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://ew.com/movies/2018/07/15/bruce-willis-die-hard-not-christmas-movie/ | title = Bruce Willis declares 'Die Hard is not a Christmas movie' | first=  Mike | last = Miller | date = July 15, 2018 | accessdate = December 18, 2018 | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] }}</ref> Acknowledging the debate over this, 20th Century Fox released a special ''Die Hard - Christmas Edition'' home media release in December 2018 (during the film's 30th anniversary), including a [[re-cut trailer]] to present the film as a heartwarming Christmas story.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/die-hards-trailer-recut-as-zany-christmas-comedy-t/1100-6463992/ | title = Die Hard's Trailer Recut As Zany Christmas Comedy To Celebrate 30th Anniversary | first=  Matt | last = Elfring |date = December 18, 2018 | accessdate = December 18, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"AccoBMI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/20031119_bmi_mourns_loss_of_composer_michael_kamen |title=BMI Mourns Loss of Composer Michael Kamen |publisher=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.]] |date=November 18, 2003 |accessdate=July 8, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209183104/http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/20031119_bmi_mourns_loss_of_composer_michael_kamen |archivedate=December 9, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BOMGeneral\">{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/title/tt0095016/ |title=Die Hard |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=October 30, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CastReynolds\">{{cite web|first=Tanya |last=Gharemani |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/06/a-history-of-iconic-roles-that-famous-actors-turned-down/burt-reynolds-as-john-mcclane |title=A History of Iconic Roles That Famous Actors Turned Down |publisher=Complex Media |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=June 23, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627152714/http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/06/a-history-of-iconic-roles-that-famous-actors-turned-down/burt-reynolds-as-john-mcclane |archivedate=June 27, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevMisc\">{{cite web|first=Jeremy |last=Kirk |url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/31-things-we-learned-from-the-die-hard-commentary-track-540a42ca0d2f/ |title=31 Things We Learned From the 'Die Hard' Commentary Track |publisher=Reject Media, LLC |work=Film School Rejects |date=July 19, 2011 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524170317/http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/features/31-things-we-learned-from-the-die-hard-commentary-track.php |archivedate=May 24, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevOtherActors\">{{cite web|first=Meriah |last=Doty |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/blogs/movie-talk/actors-turned-down-die-hard-003953140.html |title=Actors who turned down 'Die Hard' |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |work=Yahoo! Movies |date=February 13, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625133910/http://movies.yahoo.com/blogs/movie-talk/actors-turned-down-die-hard-003953140.html |archivedate=June 25, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevWillisSalary\">{{cite web|first=Aljean |last=Harmetz |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1988-02-18/features/8803310415_1_die-hard-star-movie |title=Bruce Willis Will 'Die Hard' For $5 Million |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=February 18, 1988 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913000651/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1988-02-18/features/8803310415_1_die-hard-star-movie |archivedate=September 13, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LegacyEmpire\">[http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=17 The 100 Greatest Movie Characters| 17. Hans Gruber | Empire] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107045531/http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=17 |date=2011-11-07 }}. www.empireonline.com (2006-12-05). Retrieved on 2011-01-14.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/die-hard | title=Die Hard | website = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate=July 7, 2013 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921084954/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/die-hard|archivedate=2010-09-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Oscars1989\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1989 |title=The 61st Academy Awards (1989) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-10-16 |work=oscars.org |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706095646/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/61st-winners.html |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/heather-graham-during-die-hard-los-angeles-premiere-july-12-news-photo/106860681 |title=\"Die Hard\" Los Angeles Premiere - July 12, 1988 |publisher=[[Carlyle Group]] |work=[[Getty Images]] |date=July 12, 1988 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023061953/http://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/heather-graham-during-die-hard-los-angeles-premiere-july-12-news-photo/106860681 |archivedate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/die_hard/ |title=Die Hard (1988) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=July 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171221005952/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/die_hard/ |archive-date=2017-12-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Runtime\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/die-hard-5 |title=DIE HARD |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=August 8, 1988 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023060246/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/die-hard-5 |archivedate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Die Hard (film)}}\n* {{IMDb title|0095016|Die Hard}}\n* {{mojo title|diehard|Die Hard}}\n* {{metacritic film|die-hard|Die Hard}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|die_hard|Die Hard}}\n\n{{Die Hard}}\n{{John McTiernan}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States|1980s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Die Hard}}\n[[Category:Die Hard]]\n[[Category:1988 films]]\n[[Category:1980s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s heist films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American heist films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Los Angeles Police Department]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Kamen]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John McTiernan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Joel Silver]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films about hostage takings]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jeb Stuart]]\n[[Category:Silver Pictures films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n[[Category:1980s Christmas films]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1988 action film|the film series it launched|Die Hard (film series)|other uses}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Short description|1988 American action film directed by John McTiernan}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Die Hard\n| image          = Die hard.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[John McTiernan]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lawrence Gordon (producer)|Lawrence Gordon]]\n* [[Joel Silver]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jeb Stuart (writer)|Jeb Stuart]]\n* [[Steven E. de Souza]]\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Nothing Lasts Forever (Thorp novel)|Nothing Lasts Forever]]''|[[Roderick Thorp]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Bruce Willis]]\n* [[Alan Rickman]]\n* [[Alexander Godunov]]\n* [[Bonnie Bedelia]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Michael Kamen]]\n| cinematography = [[Jan de Bont]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Frank J. Urioste]]\n* [[John F. Link]]\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Gordon Company\n* [[Silver Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1988|07|12|Los Angeles|1988|07|15|United States}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes<ref name=\"Runtime\"/>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $28 million<ref name=\"BOMGeneral\"/>\n| gross          = $141.5 million<ref name=\"BOMGeneral\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Die Hard''''' is a 1988 American [[action thriller film]] directed by [[John McTiernan]], written by [[Jeb Stuart (writer)|Jeb Stuart]] and [[Steven E. de Souza]]. Based on [[Roderick Thorp]]'s 1979 novel ''[[Nothing Lasts Forever (Thorp novel)|Nothing Lasts Forever]]'', it was produced by the Gordon Company and [[Silver Pictures]], and distributed by [[20th Century Fox]]. The film follows off-duty [[New York City Police Department]] officer [[John McClane]] ([[Bruce Willis]]) who is caught in a Los Angeles skyscraper on Christmas Eve during a heist led by criminal mastermind [[Hans Gruber (character)|Hans Gruber]] ([[Alan Rickman]]).\n\nMade for $28 million, ''Die Hard'' grossed over $141 million theatrically worldwide. Turning Willis into an action star, the film became a [[metonym]] for an action film in which a lone hero fights overwhelming odds. The film's success spurred creation of the ''[[Die Hard (film series)|Die Hard]]'' franchise, which includes four sequels, a number of video games, and a comic book. In 2017, it was selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]]. ''Die Hard'' has been named one of the [[List of films considered the best#Action|best action]] and [[List of films considered the best#Christmas|Christmas-themed films ever made]].<ref name=\"pajiba\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pajiba.com/guides/the-best-action-films-of-all-time.php | title=Die Hard is #1 according to Pajiba.com | publisher=Pajiba.com | accessdate=November 2, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101174309/http://www.pajiba.com/guides/the-best-action-films-of-all-time.php | archive-date=2011-11-01 | url-status=live | date=2007-05-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN1448232520070615|title=\"Die Hard\" tops magazine list of best action films|work=[[Reuters]]|date=2007-06-15|access-date=2017-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715005610/http://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN1448232520070615|archive-date=2009-07-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/empire-30-greatest-christmas-movies/|title=The 30 Best Christmas Movies Ever|work=Empire|accessdate=8 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006232422/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/empire-30-greatest-christmas-movies/|archive-date=2016-10-06|url-status=live}}</ref> The film also ranks {{Numero|20}} on [[Empire (film magazine)|''Empire'']]{{'}}s 2017 list of the 100 greatest movies of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-movies/|title=The 100 Greatest Movies|website=Empire|access-date=2018-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013202030/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-movies/|archive-date=2018-10-13|url-status=live|date=2018-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- PER WP:FILMPLOT, PLOT SUMMARIES FOR FEATURE FILMS SHOULD BE BETWEEN 400 AND 700 WORDS. -->\nOn Christmas Eve, [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]] detective John McClane arrives in [[Los Angeles]], intending to reconcile with his estranged wife, Holly, at the Christmas party of her employer, the Nakatomi Corporation. McClane is driven to the party by Argyle, a limousine driver. While McClane changes clothes, the party is disrupted by the arrival of a ex-[[West Germany|West German]] radical [[Hans Gruber (character)|Hans Gruber]] and his team: Karl Vreski and his brother Tony, Theo, Franco, Alexander, Marco, Kristoff, Eddie, Uli, Heinrich, Fritz, and James. The group seizes the tower, disables communication to the outside world, and secures those inside as hostages except for McClane, who slips away, and Argyle, who gets stranded in the garage.\n\nGruber interrogates Nakatomi executive Joseph Takagi for the code to the building's vault and reveals that he plans to steal $640 million in [[bearer bond]]s, with the terrorist act merely a distraction. Takagi refuses to cooperate and is killed by Gruber. McClane secretly watches, escapes, and sets off a fire alarm in an attempt to alert authorities. Eddie assures the fire department it is a false alarm. Gruber sends Tony to investigate. McClane kills Tony, pocketing his weapon and radio, which he then uses to alert the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]], who suspect McClane of making a prank call. Sgt. Al Powell is sent to investigate. Gruber sends Heinrich and Marco to stop McClane, who kills them both. Powell arrives, and finding nothing unusual, he prepares to leave, but McClane drops Marco's corpse onto his patrol car to gain his attention. Powell summons the LAPD, who lay siege to the building. McClane steals Heinrich's bag containing [[C-4 (explosive)|C-4 explosives]] and detonators.\n\nJames and Alexander use anti-tank missiles to disable a [[SWAT]] [[M8 Greyhound|armored car]] before McClane drops C-4 attached to an office chair and computer down the elevator shaft, blowing up their floor and killing them. Holly's coworker, Harry Ellis, attempts to mediate between Hans and McClane for the return of the detonators. McClane refuses, prompting Gruber to execute Ellis. While checking explosives attached to the roof, Gruber encounters McClane. Gruber masquerades as an escaped hostage; McClane offers him a gun and Gruber attempts to shoot McClane, but the gun is empty. Karl, Franco, and Fritz arrive; McClane kills Fritz and Franco but is forced to abandon the detonators.\n\nFBI agents take command of the siege, ordering the building's power shut off; this, as Gruber anticipated, disables the vault's final lock. Gruber demands a helicopter on the rooftop for transport to the Los Angeles airport, but the FBI prepare to double-cross him by sending two helicopter gunships. McClane discovers that Gruber intends to detonate the explosives on the roof, faking the deaths of his team so they can escape with the bearer bonds. While making final preparations, Gruber sees a news report by intrusive reporter Richard Thornburg that features McClane's children and deduces from a desk photo that McClane is Holly's husband. The criminals order the hostages to the roof, but Gruber takes Holly with him to use against McClane, who subdues Karl in a fight before heading up to the roof. After killing Uli, he sends the hostages downstairs as the FBI helicopters appear and shoot at McClane, believing him to be a terrorist. Gruber detonates the explosives, destroying the roof and one helicopter; McClane barely survives.\n\nTheo retrieves their getaway vehicle, an ambulance before Argyle rams it with the limo and knocks Theo unconscious. A weary McClane finds Holly with Gruber and his remaining men, Eddie and Kristoff. After knocking Kristoff unconscious, McClane confronts Gruber and is ordered to surrender his submachine gun. McClane does this to spare Holly but distracts Gruber and Eddie by laughing, allowing him to grab a concealed pistol taped to his back that contains two bullets. McClane wounds Gruber and kills Eddie; Gruber crashes through a window but grabs onto Holly's wrist. Gruber makes a last-ditch attempt to kill the pair, but McClane removes Holly's wristwatch, and Gruber falls to his death.\n\nOutside, McClane and Holly meet Powell. Karl emerges and attempts to shoot McClane, but is killed by Powell. Argyle crashes through the parking garage door in the limo. Thornburg arrives and attempts to interview McClane, but Holly punches him before she and McClane leave the area with Argyle.\n\n==Cast==\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = horizontal\n   | footer = Bruce Willis in 2010 (left) and Alan Rickman in 2011; ''Die Hard'' was Rickman's first cinema appearance and Willis's second leading role in a major Hollywood production.\n   | image1 = Bruce Willis by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n   | width1 = 164\n   | image2 = Alan Rickman BAM 2011-01-15 n1.jpg\n   | width2 = 154\n  }}\n* [[Bruce Willis]] as [[John McClane]], a streetwise New York cop who has come to Los Angeles to reconcile with his wife\n* [[Alan Rickman]] as [[Hans Gruber (character)|Hans Gruber]], an extremist recently expelled from a West German political terrorist group and the leader of the terrorists\n* [[Alexander Godunov]] as Karl Vreski, Hans's second-in-command and Tony's brother\n* [[Bonnie Bedelia]] as [[John McClane#Family|Holly Gennero-McClane]], John's estranged wife\n* [[Reginald VelJohnson]] as Sgt. Al Powell\n* [[Paul Gleason]] as Dwayne T. Robinson, the Deputy Chief of Police\n* [[De'voreaux White]] as Argyle, John's limousine driver\n* [[William Atherton]] as Richard Thornburg, an arrogant reporter\n* [[Clarence Gilyard]] as Theo, Hans's tech specialist\n* [[Hart Bochner]] as Harry Ellis, a sleazy Nakatomi executive\n* [[James Shigeta]] as Joseph Yoshinobu Takagi, Nakatomi's head executive\n\nAdditional cast includes Hans's henchmen: Bruno Doyon as Franco, [[Andreas Wisniewski]] as Tony Vreski, Joey Plewa as Alexander, [[Lorenzo Caccialanza]] as Marco, Gerard Bonn as Kristoff, [[Dennis Hayden (actor)|Dennis Hayden]] as Eddie, [[Al Leong]] as Uli, Gary Roberts as Heinrich, Hans Buhringer as Fritz, and [[Wilhelm von Homburg]] as James. [[Robert Davi]] and [[Grand L. Bush]] appear as FBI Special Agent Big Johnson and Agent Little Johnson, respectively, [[Tracy Reiner]] appears as Thornburg's assistant, and [[Taylor Fry]] and Noah Land make minor appearances as McClane's children [[John McClane#Lucy McClane|Lucy McClane]] and [[John McClane#John \"Jack\" McClane Jr.|John Jr.]]\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Foxplaza la.jpg|thumb|right|[[Fox Plaza (Los Angeles)|Fox Plaza]], which served as the setting for Nakatomi Plaza]]\n\nProduced by Lawrence Gordon and Joel Silver, the film is based on [[Roderick Thorp]]'s 1979 novel ''[[Nothing Lasts Forever (Thorp novel)|Nothing Lasts Forever]]'', the sequel to 1966's ''[[The Detective (novel)|The Detective]]''. The latter novel was adapted into a 1968 [[The Detective (1968 film)|film of the same name]] starring [[Frank Sinatra]] and was a box-office success. When a movie based on Thorp's sequel went into production, the studio was contractually obligated to offer Sinatra the lead role in ''Die Hard''.<ref name=Independent1/> Sinatra, then in his early 70s, turned down the project.<ref name=Independent1/> The story was then changed to have no connection to ''The Detective''.<ref name=Independent1/> [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] declined the role as he wished to broaden his appeal by attempting comedy in what eventually became ''[[Twins (1988 film)|Twins]]''. Although it has been rumored that at this point the project was repurposed to be a sequel to Schwarzenegger's 1985 action film ''[[Commando (1985 film)|Commando]]'', scriptwriter de Souza has denied this.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bristolbadfilmclub.co.uk/2015/03/19/exclusive-interview-part-2-steven-e-desouza-writerdirector-of-street-fighter/|title=Exclusive Interview (Part 2): Steven E. DeSouza (writer/director of Street Fighter)|work=Bristol Bad Film Club|access-date=2015-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329123136/http://www.bristolbadfilmclub.co.uk/2015/03/19/exclusive-interview-part-2-steven-e-desouza-writerdirector-of-street-fighter/|archive-date=2015-03-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> De Souza has said he wrote the script as if Hans Gruber were the protagonist. \"If he had not planned the robbery and put it together, Bruce Willis would have just gone to the party and reconciled or not with his wife. You should sometimes think about looking at your movie through the point of view of the villain who is really driving the narrative.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://creativescreenwriting.com/there-is-no-such-thing-as-an-action-movie-steven-e-de-souza-on-screenwriting/|title=\"There is no such thing as an action movie.\" Steven E. de Souza on Screenwriting|last=Frazier|first=Dan|date=August 24, 2015|publisher=Creative Screenwriting|accessdate=August 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915041138/http://creativescreenwriting.com/there-is-no-such-thing-as-an-action-movie-steven-e-de-souza-on-screenwriting/|archive-date=2015-09-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Schwarzenegger, the role was offered to a variety of other actors, including [[Richard Gere]], [[Clint Eastwood]], [[Burt Reynolds]], [[Sylvester Stallone]], [[Harrison Ford]], [[Don Johnson]], [[Nick Nolte]], [[Mel Gibson]] and [[Richard Dean Anderson]], all of whom turned it down.<ref name=\"DevOtherActors\"/><ref name=\"CastReynolds\"/> Fast running out of options, demographic data from [[CinemaScore]] helped persuade the studio, the producers and director [[John McTiernan]] to offer the role to Bruce Willis.<ref name=\"lawrence20160830\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/neon/las-vegan-s-polling-company-keeps-tabs-hollywood |title=Las Vegan's polling company keeps tabs on Hollywood |last=Lawrence |first=Christopher |date=2016-08-30 |newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal |access-date=2016-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224100303/http://www.reviewjournal.com/neon/las-vegan-s-polling-company-keeps-tabs-hollywood |archive-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAt the time, Willis was largely known for his comedic role as detective David Addison on the television series ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'' and also had co-starred in the 1987 comedy film ''[[Blind Date (1987 film)|Blind Date]]'' directed by [[Blake Edwards]]. Willis initially turned down the role due to his contractual commitments to ''Moonlighting''. However, after his co-star [[Cybill Shepherd]] became pregnant, ''Moonlighting'' was shut down for 11 weeks which provided sufficient time for Willis to work on ''Die Hard''.<ref name=Independent1>{{cite news |last= Power |first= Ed  |title= Die Hard at 30: How the every-dude action movie defied expectations and turned Bruce Willis into a star |newspaper= The Independent |date= November 26, 2018 |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/die-hard-at-30-anniversary-bruce-willis-john-mcclane-action-movie-christmas-john-mctiernan-a8642466.html |accessdate= November 27, 2018}}</ref> Willis was paid $5 million to star in the film, a figure virtually unheard of at the time for an actor who had, up to that point in time, starred in only one moderately successful film, and normally only paid to major stars such as [[Dustin Hoffman]] and [[Warren Beatty]]. Then-20th Century Fox president [[Leonard Goldberg]] justified the cost, stating the film was reliant on its lead actor, while other sources within the studio would state that Fox was desperate for a star for ''Die Hard'', intended to be its big summer action blockbuster, especially since they had already been turned down by so many other suitable actors.<ref name=\"DevWillisSalary\"/> As the studio didn't believe in Willis's action star appeal the marketing campaign's initial billboards and posters reflected this, and Willis's face was not a focal point,<ref name=\"DevOtherActors\"/> consistent with CinemaScore's suggestion to emphasize the film's action instead of a star without experience in such films.{{r|lawrence20160830}}\n\nWillis's first day on set was on November 2, 1987, when they shot the nighttime scene of him jumping with a fire hose around his waist as an explosion occurred behind  what appeared to be the top of the Nakatomi tower behind him, following the completion of that day's filming on ''Moonlighting'' at Lorimar Studios (now [[Sony Pictures Studios]]) in [[Culver City, California]].<ref name=Independent1/>, In reality, he jumped from the roof of a five-story parking garage onto an airbag. The force of the explosion blew him out to the very edge of the airbag. When upon completing the stunt Willis inquired why they hadn't filmed such a dangerous scene at the end of production, he was told that if they had, then they would have run the expensive risk of having to reshoot the whole movie with another actor.<ref name=Independent1/>\n\nMcTiernan did not want the villains to be terrorists, considering them too mean. He chose to avoid the terrorists' politics in favor of making them thieves in pursuit of monetary gain, believing it would make the film more suitable for summer entertainment. The film's ending had not been finalized by the time filming had begun; one result is that the truck depicted as transporting the terrorists to the building is too small to house the ambulance that was later revealed to be inside it. Other scenes also lacked context: [[production designer]] Jackson De Govia had built the building's computer room before they knew what it would be used for. Likewise, the character of McClane had not been fully realized until almost halfway through production, when McTiernan and Willis decided that he was a man who did not like himself very much, but was doing the best he could in a bad situation. In the original script, ''Die Hard'' took place over three days, but McTiernan was inspired to have it take place over a single night by Shakespeare's ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]''.<ref name=\"DevMisc\"/>\n\nThe corporate headquarters of [[20th Century Fox]], [[Fox Plaza (Los Angeles)|Fox Plaza]] in [[Century City]] (which had opened a year prior to the film's release), serves as the film's setting for both external and internal scenes. At the time of filming, the building was still under construction, and the setting for a scene of McClane exploring an unfinished floor complete with construction equipment was real\u2014after filming (and construction) was completed, the room used for that scene became the office of former President [[Ronald Reagan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/inside-ronald-reagans-die-hard-635440 |title=Inside Ronald Reagan's Die Hard Office |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=2018-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005190728/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/inside-ronald-reagans-die-hard-635440 |archive-date=2018-10-05 |url-status=live }}</ref> De Govia came up with the idea to use the building. The Nakatomi building's 30th floor, where the hostages are held, was a recreation of the [[Frank Lloyd Wright]]-designed house [[Fallingwater]], including a large rock with water dripping from it. Govia's inspiration came from Japanese corporations of the time buying up American products, his rationale being that Nakatomi had bought Fallingwater and reassembled it in their own building. The building's logo originally was too reminiscent of a [[swastika]] for McTiernan; the final design is closer to a Samurai warrior's helmet. A 380-foot-long [[matte painting]] provided the city backdrop as viewed from inside the Nakatomi building's 30th floor. It featured animated lights and other lighting techniques to present both moving traffic and day and night cycles. {{as of|2011}}, the painting is still in Fox's inventory and is sometimes used in other films. For the film's night exterior shots, cinematographer [[Jan de Bont]] employed a 50mm T1.1 anamorphic lens - the fastest such lens available - and push-processed the film by an additional stop in order to capture the city lights.\n\nThe scene in which the SWAT [[M8 Greyhound|Greyhound armored vehicle]] knocks over a stair railing at the front of Fox Plaza required months of negotiations with Fox to gain approval. The end helicopter scene took six months of preparation, and the production was given only two hours in which to film it. It took three attempts above Fox Plaza, nine camera crews, and no one but crew members was allowed within 500 feet of the line of flight. The scene of McClane falling down a ventilation shaft and catching onto a lower opening was the result of an accident after Willis' stunt man fell. Editor [[Frank J. Urioste]] chose to use the unintentional scene in the final film.<ref name=\"DevMisc\"/>\n\n''Die Hard'' was [[Alan Rickman]]'s first feature film role.<ref name=\"LegacyEmpire\"/> Rickman was cast after producer Joel Silver saw his performance as Vicomte de Valmont in the Broadway run of ''Les Liaisons Dangereuses''.<ref name=Independent1/> For his death scene, he was dropped {{convert|70|ft}} on a [[Chroma key|blue screen]] set. The shot used was the first take; Rickman was dropped sooner than he had been told he would be, so the look of fear on his face is genuine, an act that reportedly angered the actor.<ref name=\"DevMisc\"/> The DVD text commentary track reveals that the shooting script did not originally include the meeting between McClane and Gruber pretending to be a hostage; it was only written in when it was discovered that Rickman could perform a convincing American accent.\n\n==Release==\nThe premiere of ''Die Hard'' took place on July 12, 1988, at the AVCO theater in Los Angeles, California.<ref name=\"Premiere\"/>\n''Die Hard'' had its inaugural British screening at the London Film Festival on 27 November 1988.<ref name=Independent1/>\n\n===Box office===\n''Die Hard'' opened in limited release in 21 theaters on July 15, 1988, earning $601,851\u2014an average of $28,659 per theater. The film began a wide release in North America on July 20, 1988, earning approximately $7.1 million from 1,276 theaters\u2014an average of $5,568 per theater\u2014finishing as the weekend's number three film. By the time ''Die Hard'' ended its theatrical run, it had earned $83 million in North America and a further $57.7 million from markets elsewhere, totaling $140.7 million.<ref name=\"BOMGeneral\"/>\n\n===Home media===\n''Die Hard'' was released on [[DVD-Video|DVD]] on June 19, 2007, a [[Blu-ray]] Disc release followed on November 20, 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/669/Die-Hard.html|title=Die Hard DVD Release Date|website=DVDs Release Dates|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523095357/https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/669/Die-Hard.html|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released on [[4K resolution|4K]] [[Ultra-high-definition television|UHD]] Blu-ray on May 15, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultrahd.highdefdigest.com/56659/diehard4kultrahdblurayfrenchimport.html|title=High Def Digest {{!}} Blu-ray and Games News and Reviews in High Definition|website=ultrahd.highdefdigest.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523095717/https://ultrahd.highdefdigest.com/56659/diehard4kultrahdblurayfrenchimport.html|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n{{expand section|date=February 2018}}\nOn release, ''Die Hard'' drew ambivalent reviews from critics.<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|title=Die Hard (1988)|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/55749|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=February 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211071728/https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/55749|archive-date=2018-02-11|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave it a less-than-flattering review, rating it a mere two stars out of a possible four. Despite considering it well made and performed (particularly Rickman's role) Ebert criticized the stupidity of Gleason's deputy police chief character, claiming that \"all by himself he successfully undermines the last half of the movie.\"<ref>{{cite news |title = Die Hard |url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19880715/REVIEWS/807150301/1023 |publisher = [[Roger Ebert]], [[Chicago Sun-Times]] |accessdate = December 17, 2009 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110302012747/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F19880715%2FREVIEWS%2F807150301%2F1023 |archive-date = 2011-03-02 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nRetrospective reviews have been much more positive. On [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 93% based on 76 reviews, and an average rating of 8.53/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Its many imitators (and sequels) have never come close to matching the taut thrills of the definitive holiday action classic.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\"/> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 70 out of 100, based on 13 critics, which indicates \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"Metacritic\" /> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nordine|first1=Michael|title=Best CinemaScore Ratings: Movies With an 'A+' From the Audience|url=http://www.indiewire.com/gallery/best-cinema-score-rating-movies-a-audience-score/#!10/die-hard-1988-2/|accessdate=December 4, 2017|work=[[indieWire]]|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=November 26, 2017|quote=''Die Hard'' is located page 10 of the article's photo gallery.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204223007/http://www.indiewire.com/gallery/best-cinema-score-rating-movies-a-audience-score/#!10/die-hard-1988-2/|archive-date=2017-12-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Critics' rankings====\nSome critics have ranked the film on respective lists of the all-time best Christmas films (see below, [[Die Hard#Status as a Christmas film|Status as a Christmas film]], for further discussion):\n* [[Digital Spy]] \u2013 #5<ref>{{cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|title=Muppet Christmas Carol tops Digital Spy favourite Christmas film poll|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a356141/muppet-christmas-carol-tops-digital-spy-favourite-christmas-film-poll.html|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|date=December 19, 2011|accessdate=December 24, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108014025/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a356141/muppet-christmas-carol-tops-digital-spy-favourite-christmas-film-poll.html|archive-date=2012-01-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' \u2013 #1<ref>{{Cite news |title=The 30 Best Christmas Movies Ever |url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p29 |work=empireonline.com |publisher=Bauer Consumer Media |date=December 2010 |accessdate=2011-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322165455/http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p29 |archive-date=2012-03-22 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' \u2013 #4<ref>{{cite news|title=20 Top Christmas Movies Ever|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20317203_20449281_20888961,00.html|first=Chris|last=Nashawaty|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=2011-12-26|access-date=2014-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220044906/http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20317203_20449281_20888961,00.html|archive-date=2014-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[Forbes]]'' \u2013 #1<ref>{{cite news|title=Elf #7 Forbes best christmas movies of all time|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2011/12/14/top-ten-best-christmas-movies-of-all-time/|first=Mark|last=Hughes|access-date=2017-08-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115212209/https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2011/12/14/top-ten-best-christmas-movies-of-all-time/|archive-date=2017-11-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Guardian]]'' \u2013 #8<ref>{{cite news|title=Guardian Greatest christmas movies Elf #4|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/nov/29/christmas-favourite-film-poll-wonderful|publisher=HanMan|access-date=2016-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217143938/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/nov/29/christmas-favourite-film-poll-wonderful|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2011-11-29|last1=Child|first1=Ben}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' \u2013 #4<ref>{{cite news|title=Elf #6 Greatest xmas film of all time|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/best-christmas-movies-grinch-rudolph-395660#4-die-hard|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Aaron|last=Couch|access-date=2014-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206234656/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/best-christmas-movies-grinch-rudolph-395660#4-die-hard|archive-date=2015-02-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[San Francisco Chronicle|San Francisco Gate]]'' \u2013 #1<ref>{{cite news|title=Today's Special: Best Christmas Movies of All Time (Updated!)|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/thebigevent/2011/12/22/todays-special-best-christmas-movies-of-all-time/#photo-34458|work=The San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=2014-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220043810/http://blog.sfgate.com/thebigevent/2011/12/22/todays-special-best-christmas-movies-of-all-time/#photo-34458|archive-date=2014-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe film was nominated for four [[61st Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]: [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Effects Editing]] ([[Stephen Hunter Flick]] and [[Richard Shorr]]), [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound|Best Sound]] ([[Don Bassman|Don J. Bassman]], [[Kevin F. Cleary]], [[Richard Overton (sound engineer)|Richard Overton]] and [[Al Overton Jr.]]) and [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]] ([[Richard Edlund]], [[Al DiSarro]], [[Brent Boates]] and Thaine Morris).<ref name=\"Oscars1989\"/> [[Michael Kamen]]'s score earned him a [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI TV/Film Music Award]] in 1989.<ref name=\"AccoBMI\"/>\n\n==Music==\nThe main theme from the finale of [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]]'s [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|9th Symphony]] (commonly known as \"Ode to Joy\") is featured prominently in [[Michael Kamen]]'s score throughout the film, in many guises and variations (mostly as a [[leitmotif]] for Gruber and the terrorists), and thematic variations on \"[[Singin' in the Rain (song)|Singin' in the Rain]]\" are also featured, as the theme for the character Theo. McTiernan said that he incorporated those themes into the film's soundtrack as an homage to [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[A Clockwork Orange (film)|A Clockwork Orange]]'' (which featured both pieces of music).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amc.com/talk/2008/02/die-hards-debt|title=Die Hard's Debt to A Clockwork Orange and Beethoven|access-date=2017-12-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229233731/http://www.amc.com/talk/2008/02/die-hards-debt|archive-date=2017-12-29|url-status=live}}</ref> Basing his score around thematic variations on well-known pieces is a concept that Kamen previously used in ''[[Brazil (1985 film)|Brazil]]''. [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]'s [[Brandenburg Concertos|''Brandenburg Concerto No. 3'']] is playing during the party sequence near the film's beginning.\n\nAs the film has a Christmas setting, the score also features sleigh bells in some cues, as well as the Christmas pop standard \"[[Winter Wonderland]]\". Two 1987 pop songs are used as source music: near the film's beginning, limousine driver Argyle plays the rap song \"[[Christmas in Hollis]]\", performed by [[Run-DMC]], and, later, while talking on the phone in the limousine, Argyle is listening to [[Stevie Wonder]]'s \"[[Skeletons (Stevie Wonder song)|Skeletons]]\". The end credits of the film begin with the Christmas song \"[[Let It Snow! Let It Snow! Let It Snow!]]\" (performed by [[Vaughn Monroe]]) and continue with Beethoven's 9th Symphony.\n\nThe film's final four minutes were tracked with music from two other Twentieth Century Fox features; these were temporary tracks which the studio decided to leave in the film. The music heard when McClane and Powell see each other for the first time is from [[John Scott (composer)|John Scott]]'s score for the 1987 film ''[[Man on Fire (1987 film)|Man on Fire]]''. When Karl appears with his rifle, McTiernan decided that he did not like Kamen's produced music for the scene and chose to use a piece of temporary score that the production had purchased. The piece was part of the score composed by [[James Horner]] for the 1986 science fiction action film ''[[Aliens (film)|Aliens]]''.<ref name=\"DevMisc\"/>\n\nSimilarly to ''Aliens'', the score by Michael Kamen was heavily edited, with music samples looped over and over and cues added to scenes. The most notable example is the \"brass blast\" heard when John slams the chair at the window as he confronts Marco, then Heinrich appears and he kills him, and later when Hans Gruber falls to his death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/die_hard.html|title=Filmtracks: Die Hard (Michael Kamen)|accessdate=2009-07-10|publisher=Filmtracks.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701235511/http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/die_hard.html|archive-date=2009-07-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe score as heard in the film was released by [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]] in February 2002, but was limited to 3,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.varesesarabande.com/details.asp?pid=VCL%2D0202%2D1004 |title=Die Hard by Michael Kamen |accessdate=2009-07-10 |publisher=Varesesarabande.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016021428/http://www.varesesarabande.com/details.asp?pid=VCL-0202-1004 |archivedate=October 16, 2007 }}</ref> It was subsequently reissued by La-La Land Records in November 2011, in a two-disc limited edition of 3,500 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lalalandrecords.com/Die.html|title=Die Hard by Michael Kamen|accessdate=2014-05-29|website=lalalandrecords.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529085641/http://www.lalalandrecords.com/Die.html|archivedate=2014-05-29}}</ref> In addition to the Kamen score, this release also includes the Monroe and Beethoven end credits pieces, Run-DMC's \"Christmas in Hollis,\" and the John Scott track from ''Man on Fire''.\n\n==Legacy==\nThe film spawned four sequels: ''[[Die Hard 2]]'' (1990), ''[[Die Hard with a Vengeance]]'' (1995), ''[[Live Free or Die Hard]]'' (2007), and ''[[A Good Day to Die Hard]]'' (2013). In July 2007, Bruce Willis donated the undershirt worn in the film to the [[National Museum of American History]] at the [[Smithsonian Institution]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/willis.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120909191903/http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/willis.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 9, 2012 |title=Die Hard Donation |last1=Crawford |first1=Amy |date=July 1, 2007 |publisher=Smithsonian.com |accessdate=September 10, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n''Die Hard'' established what would be a common formula for action films over the next decade, featuring a lone [[everyman]] against a colorful terrorist character in an isolated setting.<ref name=\"guardian 30th\">{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/12/die-hard-30th-anniversary-quintessential-action-movie | title = Die Hard at 30: how it remains the quintessential American action movie | first = Scott | last = Tobias | date = July 12, 2018 | accessdate = July 12, 2018 | work = [[The Guardian]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180712111933/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/12/die-hard-30th-anniversary-quintessential-action-movie | archive-date = 2018-07-12 | url-status = live }}</ref> Several of these films that followed this formula were often referred to as \"''Die Hard'' on a _____\", such as ''[[Under Siege]]'' (1992, \"''Die Hard'' on a battleship\"), ''[[Passenger 57]]'' (1992, \"''Die Hard'' on a plane\") and ''[[Speed (1994 film)|Speed]]'' (1994, \"''Die Hard'' on a bus\").<ref name=\"guardian 30th\"/><ref name = \"Die Hard on a bus\">{{Cite book | last = Weinberger | first = Everett | title = Wannabe: A Would-Be Player's Misadventures in Hollywood | publisher = Macmillan | year = 1997 | page = 52 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=m6IFlodX4E4C&pg=PA52 | isbn = 0-312-15708-8 }}</ref> Such a trend would continue until films like ''[[The Rock (film)|The Rock]]'' (1996, also dubbed \"''Die Hard'' on [[Alcatraz Island|an island]]\") changed the tone and feel of how action movies going forward were made, and which further changed with the evolution of CGI effects exemplified by ''[[The Matrix]]'' (1999).<ref name=\"guardian 30th\"/><ref>''The Movies of the Eighties'' (1990) by Ron Base and David Haslam.</ref> Other 1990s action films featuring the Die Hard scenario include ''[[Cliffhanger (film)|Cliffhanger]]'', ''[[Under Siege 2: Dark Territory]]'', ''[[Sudden Death (1995 film)|Sudden Death]]'', ''[[Broken Arrow (1996 film)|Broken Arrow]]'', ''[[Executive Decision]]'', ''[[Con Air]]'', ''[[Speed 2: Cruise Control]]'', and ''[[Air Force One (film)|Air Force One]]''. Scott Tobias of ''[[The Guardian]]'' observed that none of these following films readily captured the complete effectiveness of the ''Die Hard'' story.<ref name=\"guardian 30th\"/>\n\nIn 2001, ''Die Hard'' was listed at #39 on AFI's ''[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Thrills|100 Years... 100 Thrills]]'', a list of America's most heart-pounding films.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/thrills100.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Thrills |accessdate=2014-06-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328082214/http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/thrills100.pdf |archive-date=2014-03-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2003, Hans Gruber was listed at #46 on ''[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains|the AFI's 100 Years... 100 Heroes and Villains]]'' list.<ref>[http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/handv100.pdf ''AFI'S 100 YEARS...100 HEROES AND VILLAINS''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328082215/http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/handv100.pdf |date=2014-03-28 }} handv100.pdf</ref> It was selected by ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine as #29 on their \"500 Greatest Movies of All Time\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/500/91.asp|title=The 500 Greatest Movies Of All Time|work=Empire|accessdate=January 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310180609/http://www.empireonline.com/500/91.asp|archive-date=2012-03-10|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, the film was selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]] as being \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-17-178/|title=2017 National Film Registry Is More Than a 'Field of Dreams'|date=December 13, 2017|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=December 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213180919/https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-17-178/|archive-date=2017-12-13|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2006, Gruber was listed as the 17th-greatest film character by ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''.<ref name=\"LegacyEmpire\"/> John McClane was placed at number 12 on the same list.<ref>[http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=12 The 100 Greatest Movie Characters| 12. John McClane | Empire] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602093301/http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=12 |date=2013-06-02 }}. empireonline.com (2006-12-05). Retrieved on 2011-01-14.</ref> In the June 22, 2007 issue of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' it was named the best action film of all time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN1448232520070615|title=\"Die Hard\" tops magazine list of best action films|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=June 15, 2007|access-date=2017-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715005610/http://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN1448232520070615|archive-date=2009-07-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Status as a Christmas film===\nIn 2010, ''Die Hard'' was voted as \"The Greatest Christmas Film of All Time\" by ''Empire''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p30|title=The 30 Best Christmas Movies Ever|publisher=Empireonline.com|accessdate=2011-01-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120055157/http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p30|archive-date=2012-01-20|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, [[IGN]] listed it at the top spot on their list of \"The Top 25 Action Movies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/the-top-25-action-movies?page=5|title=The Top 25 Action Movies|website=[[IGN]]|author=<!--Staff writers; no byline.-->|date=2012-01-09|accessdate=2016-12-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221153925/http://www.ign.com/articles/the-top-25-action-movies?page=5|archive-date=2016-12-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Debates have been had about whether or not ''Die Hard'' should be considered a Christmas film. Some feel that because the events of the film occur on Christmas Eve and its setting includes a Christmas party, that is enough to qualify it as a Christmas film, while others feel that since the film is not actually about Christmas and focuses on an action plot involving a lone police officer trying to stop terrorists, it should not be considered a Christmas film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/item/4729e8ae-ca0b-4d4a-a43a-36e29cc33296|title=People are claiming Die Hard is a Christmas film and it's tearing the internet apart|first=Tomasz|last=Frymorgen|date=28 November 2017|website=BBC Three|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224010346/http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/item/4729e8ae-ca0b-4d4a-a43a-36e29cc33296|archive-date=2017-12-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/die-hard-is-the-best-christmas-film-top-films-to-watch-holiday-poll-list-not-a8092761.html|title=Die Hard is officially not a Christmas film|work=The Independent|date=5 December 2017|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224145713/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/die-hard-is-the-best-christmas-film-top-films-to-watch-holiday-poll-list-not-a8092761.html|archive-date=2017-12-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nerdist.com/die-hard-christmas-movie/|title=Does DIE HARD Really Qualify as a Christmas Movie?|publisher=Nerdist|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223030626/https://nerdist.com/die-hard-christmas-movie/|archive-date=2017-12-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/die-hard-christmas-movie-debate-calgary-eyeopener-1.4450305|title=Why Die Hard is the ultimate Christmas movie \u2014 despite naysayers|publisher=CBC|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226162909/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/die-hard-christmas-movie-debate-calgary-eyeopener-1.4450305|archive-date=2017-12-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/tom-ward/why-die-hard-is-the-best-christmas-movie-of-all-time_b_2339117.html|title=Why Die Hard Is the Best Christmas Movie of All Time|work=Huffington Post|date=24 December 2012|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171217014838/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/tom-ward/why-die-hard-is-the-best-christmas-movie-of-all-time_b_2339117.html|archive-date=2017-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1600567/die-hard-home-alone-and-more-of-our-favorite-secret-christmas-movies/|title='Die Hard,' 'Home Alone' And More Of Our Favorite 'Secret' Christmas Movies|publisher=MTV|accessdate=27 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014130031/http://www.mtv.com/news/1600567/die-hard-home-alone-and-more-of-our-favorite-secret-christmas-movies/|archive-date=2018-10-14|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 24, 2017, screenwriter [[Steven E. de Souza]] stated on [[Twitter]] that ''Die Hard'' is a Christmas film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/die-hard-christmas-film-bruce-willis-yougov-poll-screenwriter-steven-de-souza-a8127841.html|title=Die Hard screenwriter says it is a Christmas movie: 'A woman about to give birth features prominently'|date=2017-12-25|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225214314/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/die-hard-christmas-film-bruce-willis-yougov-poll-screenwriter-steven-de-souza-a8127841.html|archive-date=2017-12-25|url-status=live}}</ref> However, at his [[Comedy Central Roast]], Willis declared \"''Die Hard'' is not a Christmas movie! It is a goddamn Bruce Willis movie!\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://ew.com/movies/2018/07/15/bruce-willis-die-hard-not-christmas-movie/ | title = Bruce Willis declares 'Die Hard is not a Christmas movie' | first=  Mike | last = Miller | date = July 15, 2018 | accessdate = December 18, 2018 | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] }}</ref> Acknowledging the debate over this, 20th Century Fox released a special ''Die Hard - Christmas Edition'' home media release in December 2018 (during the film's 30th anniversary), including a [[re-cut trailer]] to present the film as a heartwarming Christmas story.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/die-hards-trailer-recut-as-zany-christmas-comedy-t/1100-6463992/ | title = Die Hard's Trailer Recut As Zany Christmas Comedy To Celebrate 30th Anniversary | first=  Matt | last = Elfring |date = December 18, 2018 | accessdate = December 18, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"AccoBMI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/20031119_bmi_mourns_loss_of_composer_michael_kamen |title=BMI Mourns Loss of Composer Michael Kamen |publisher=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.]] |date=November 18, 2003 |accessdate=July 8, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209183104/http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/20031119_bmi_mourns_loss_of_composer_michael_kamen |archivedate=December 9, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BOMGeneral\">{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/title/tt0095016/ |title=Die Hard |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=October 30, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CastReynolds\">{{cite web|first=Tanya |last=Gharemani |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/06/a-history-of-iconic-roles-that-famous-actors-turned-down/burt-reynolds-as-john-mcclane |title=A History of Iconic Roles That Famous Actors Turned Down |publisher=Complex Media |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=June 23, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627152714/http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/06/a-history-of-iconic-roles-that-famous-actors-turned-down/burt-reynolds-as-john-mcclane |archivedate=June 27, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevMisc\">{{cite web|first=Jeremy |last=Kirk |url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/31-things-we-learned-from-the-die-hard-commentary-track-540a42ca0d2f/ |title=31 Things We Learned From the 'Die Hard' Commentary Track |publisher=Reject Media, LLC |work=Film School Rejects |date=July 19, 2011 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524170317/http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/features/31-things-we-learned-from-the-die-hard-commentary-track.php |archivedate=May 24, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevOtherActors\">{{cite web|first=Meriah |last=Doty |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/blogs/movie-talk/actors-turned-down-die-hard-003953140.html |title=Actors who turned down 'Die Hard' |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |work=Yahoo! Movies |date=February 13, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625133910/http://movies.yahoo.com/blogs/movie-talk/actors-turned-down-die-hard-003953140.html |archivedate=June 25, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevWillisSalary\">{{cite web|first=Aljean |last=Harmetz |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1988-02-18/features/8803310415_1_die-hard-star-movie |title=Bruce Willis Will 'Die Hard' For $5 Million |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=February 18, 1988 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913000651/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1988-02-18/features/8803310415_1_die-hard-star-movie |archivedate=September 13, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LegacyEmpire\">[http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=17 The 100 Greatest Movie Characters| 17. Hans Gruber | Empire] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107045531/http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=17 |date=2011-11-07 }}. www.empireonline.com (2006-12-05). Retrieved on 2011-01-14.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/die-hard | title=Die Hard | website = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate=July 7, 2013 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921084954/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/die-hard|archivedate=2010-09-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Oscars1989\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1989 |title=The 61st Academy Awards (1989) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-10-16 |work=oscars.org |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706095646/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/61st-winners.html |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/heather-graham-during-die-hard-los-angeles-premiere-july-12-news-photo/106860681 |title=\"Die Hard\" Los Angeles Premiere - July 12, 1988 |publisher=[[Carlyle Group]] |work=[[Getty Images]] |date=July 12, 1988 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023061953/http://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/heather-graham-during-die-hard-los-angeles-premiere-july-12-news-photo/106860681 |archivedate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/die_hard/ |title=Die Hard (1988) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=July 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171221005952/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/die_hard/ |archive-date=2017-12-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Runtime\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/die-hard-5 |title=DIE HARD |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=August 8, 1988 |accessdate=July 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023060246/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/die-hard-5 |archivedate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Die Hard (film)}}\n* {{IMDb title|0095016|Die Hard}}\n* {{mojo title|diehard|Die Hard}}\n* {{metacritic film|die-hard|Die Hard}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|die_hard|Die Hard}}\n\n{{Die Hard}}\n{{John McTiernan}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States|1980s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Die Hard}}\n[[Category:Die Hard]]\n[[Category:1988 films]]\n[[Category:1980s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s heist films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American heist films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Los Angeles Police Department]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Kamen]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John McTiernan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Joel Silver]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films about hostage takings]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jeb Stuart]]\n[[Category:Silver Pictures films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n[[Category:1980s Christmas films]]\n", "name_user": "106.208.142.192", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCritical reception)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Die_Hard"}
{"title_page": "John Young (astronaut)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Watts Young\n| image         = Astronaut John W. Young.jpg\n| caption       =\n| nationality   = American\n| birth_name    = John Watts Young\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1930|09|24}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2018|01|05|1930|09|24}}\n| death_place   = [[Seabrook, Texas]] U.S.\n| occupation    = [[United States Naval Aviator|Naval Aviator]], [[test pilot]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]], B.S. 1952\n| module        = {{Infobox astronaut|child =yes\n| type          = [[NASA]] astronaut\n| rank          = {{Dodseal|USNO6|25}} [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]], [[United States Navy|USN]]\n| selection     = [[List of astronauts by year of selection#1962|1962 NASA Group 2]]\n| time          = 34d 19h 39m\n| eva1          = 3\n| eva2          = 20h 14m 14s\n| mission       = [[Gemini 3]], [[Gemini 10]], [[Apollo 10]], [[Apollo 16]], [[STS-1]], [[STS-9]]\n| insignia      = [[File:Gemini3.png|45px]] [[File:Gemini 10 Insignia.svg|54px]] [[File:Apollo-10-LOGO.png|45px]] [[File:Apollo-16-LOGO.png|45px]] [[File:Sts-1-patch.png|45px]] [[File:Sts-9-patch.png|45px]]\n| Date of ret   = December 31, 2004\n| awards        = [[File:Dfc-usa.jpg|20px|link=Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]] {{CS Medal of Honor}} [[File:NASA Distinguished Service Medal.jpg|20px|link=NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n}}}}\n\n'''John Watts Young''' (September 24, 1930&nbsp;\u2013 January 5, 2018) was an American [[astronaut]], [[United States Navy|naval officer]] and [[United States Naval Aviator|aviator]], [[test pilot]], and [[aerospace engineering|aeronautical engineer]]. He became the [[List of Apollo astronauts#People who have walked on the Moon|ninth person to walk on the Moon]] as Commander of the [[Apollo 16]] mission in 1972. Young enjoyed the longest career of any astronaut, becoming the first person to fly six space missions over the course of 42 years of active [[NASA]] service.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/young.html |title=Biographical Data: John W. Young (Captain, USN Ret.) |publisher=NASA |date=August 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref> He is the only person to have piloted and commanded four different classes of spacecraft: [[Project Gemini|Gemini]], the [[Apollo Command and Service Module]], the [[Apollo Lunar Module]], and the [[Space Shuttle]].<ref name=\"sentinel20160924\">{{cite news |last1=Speck |first1=Emilee |title=Moon-walking astronaut John Young turned 86 on Saturday |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/space/go-for-launch/os-nasa-astronaut-john-young-turns-86-20160923-story.html |access-date=August 16, 2017 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=September 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965 Young flew on the [[Gemini 3|first crewed Gemini mission]], and then commanded the 1966 [[Gemini 10]] mission. In 1969 during [[Apollo 10]], he became the first person to fly solo around the Moon.<ref name=\"nasa200412007\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/vision/space/features/young_retires.html |title=From Gemini to Shuttle: John Young Retires |publisher=NASA |date=December 7, 2004 |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He then walked on the Moon and drove the [[Lunar Roving Vehicle]] on the Moon's surface during [[Apollo 16]], and is one of only three people to have [[List of Apollo astronauts|flown to the Moon]] twice.<ref name=\"npr20180106\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/01/16/505928876/gene-cernan-last-man-to-walk-on-the-moon-dies-at-82 |title=Gene Cernan, Last Man To Walk On The Moon, Dies At 82 |publisher=NPR |last1=Lewis |first1=Russell |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> \n\nYoung also commanded two flights of [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']]: [[STS-1]] in 1981, the [[Space Shuttle]] program's first launch, and [[STS-9]] in 1983. Young served as [[Chief of the Astronaut Office]] from 1974 to 1987, and retired from NASA in 2004.\n\n==Early years and education==\nYoung was born in [[San Francisco, California]], on September 24, 1930,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28981374/the_orlando_sentinel/ |title=Astronauts Could Have a Party |newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel |location=Orlando, Florida |date=February 3, 1963 |page=15 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> to parents William Hugh Young, a civil engineer,<ref name=\"nyt20180106\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/06/obituaries/john-young-dead.html |title=John Young, Who Led First Space Shuttle Mission, Dies at 87 |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Richard |last=Goldstein |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> and Wanda Howland Young.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\">{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/biographies-list/bios-y/Young-John/Young-John-Text.html |title=John Watts Young |publisher=Navy Office of Information, Biographies Branch |date=April 10, 1972}}</ref> At 18 months old, due to the [[Great Depression]], he moved with his family to [[Cartersville, Georgia|Cartersville]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]],<ref name=\"fortune20180106\">{{cite news |url=http://amp.timeinc.net/fortune/2018/01/06/astronaut-john-young-dead |title=Astronaut John Young, One of Only 12 to Walk on Moon, Dies at 87 |work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |agency=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> then to [[Orlando, Florida]], where he attended grade school and later [[Orange County Public Schools#High schools|Orlando High School]] until graduating in 1948.<ref name=\"sjg19650324\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HhpdAAAAIBAJ&pg=1598%2C4411712 |title=John Young, as Early as 1946, Displayed Interest in Rockets |work=[[St. Joseph Gazette]] |agency=Associated Press |volume=120 |issue=238 |page=6A |date=March 24, 1965 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"jwy-edu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/education.htm |title=Biography: Education |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128151906/http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/education.htm |archive-date=November 28, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Young was a [[Scouts BSA (Boy Scouts of America)|Boy Scout]] and earned the rank of [[Second Class (Boy Scouts of America)|Second Class]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scouting.org/About/FactSheets/scouting_space.aspx |title=Scouting and Space Exploration |website=Scouting.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303213130/http://www.scouting.org/about/factsheets/scouting_space.aspx |archivedate=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nYoung earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree with highest honors in [[Aerospace engineering|Aeronautical Engineering]] from the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] in 1952; while attending, he became a member of the national military honor society [[Scabbard and Blade]] and [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity.<ref name=\"fw4465\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1774&dat=19650404&id=AZscAAAAIBAJ&pg=5001,1212947 |title=Virgil Grissom and John Young: Our Trail-Blazing \"Twin\" Astronauts |work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]] |series=Family Weekly |first=John W. |last=Wasik |page=4 |date=April 4, 1965 |access-date=January 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"blueprint1952\">{{cite book |url=http://hdl.handle.net/1853/25833 |title=Blue Print |publisher=[[Georgia Institute of Technology]] |editor-first=Blount |editor-last=Boswell |volume=45 |page=108 |date=1952}}</ref>\n\n==Navy service==\n{{quote box|align=right|width=28%|quote=I got a telegram from the [[Chief of Naval Operations]] asking me not to do this anymore.|salign=right|source=\u2014Young, describing an air-to-air missile test in which he and another pilot approached each other at Mach 3 - risking destruction of both aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/navycareer.htm |title=Astronaut John W. Young - Navy Career |website=Johnwyoung.org}}</ref>}}\n\nAfter graduating from [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]] in 1952, Young entered the [[United States Navy]] through the [[Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps|Navy ROTC]] and was commissioned on June 6, 1952, as an [[ensign (rank)|ensign]].<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> He served as fire control officer on the destroyer {{USS|Laws|DD-558|6}} until June 1953 and completed a tour in the [[Sea of Japan]] during the [[Korean War]]. Following this assignment, he was sent to flight training. In January 1954, he was designated a Navy helicopter pilot.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> After receiving his [[United States Naval Aviator|aviator wings]] on December 20, 1954, he was assigned to Fighter Squadron 103 ([[VFA-103|VF-103]]) for four years, flying [[Grumman F9F Cougar]]s from {{USS|Coral Sea|CV-43|6}} and [[Vought F8U Crusader]]s from {{USS|Forrestal|CV-59|6}}.<ref name=\"nmmuseum\" />\n\nAfter training at the [[United States Naval Test Pilot School]] in 1959 with the Class 23, Young was assigned to the Naval Air Test Center at [[Naval Air Station Patuxent River]], Maryland, for three years. His test projects included evaluations of the [[Vought XF8U-3 Crusader III|XF8U-3 Crusader III]] and [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4 Phantom II]] fighter weapons systems. In 1962, he set two world time-to-climb records while flying his Phantom II, attaining {{convert|3000|m|ft|0|sp=us}} from a standing start in 34.52 seconds and {{convert|25000|m|ft|0|sp=us}} from a standing start in 227.6 seconds.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> He also served as maintenance officer of Fighter Squadron 143 ([[VFA-143|VF-143]]) from April to September 1962.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nFellow astronaut [[Charles Bolden]] described Young and [[Robert L. Gibson|Robert \"Hoot\" Gibson]] as the two best pilots he had met during his aviation career: \"Never met two people like them. Everyone else gets into an airplane; John and Hoot wear their airplane. They're just awesome\".<ref name=\"bolden20040106\">{{cite interview |title=Charles F. Bolden |date=January 6, 2004 |access-date=January 6, 2014 |last=Bolden |first=Charles F. |subjectlink=Charles Bolden |interviewer1=Johnson, Sandra |interviewer2=Wright, Rebecca |interviewer3=Ross-Nazzal, Jennifer |work=NASA Johnson Space Center Oral History Project |location=Houston, Texas |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/history/oral_histories/BoldenCF/BoldenCF_1-6-04.htm}}</ref> Young retired from the Navy as a [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] in September 1976, after 25 years.<ref name=\"nmmuseum\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nmspacemuseum.org/halloffame/detail.php?id=70 |title=Commanded the first shuttle flight, the first person to enter space six times |publisher=New Mexico Museum of Space History |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==NASA career==\n===Project Gemini===\n{{Main|Gemini 3|Gemini 10}}\n[[File:Astronaut John Young gemini 3.jpg|left|thumb|Young, age 34, as pilot of Gemini 3]]\nJoining [[NASA]] in 1962, Young was the first of the [[NASA Astronaut Group 2|Astronaut Group 2]] to fly in space, replacing [[Thomas P. Stafford]] as pilot of [[Gemini 3]] when [[Alan Shepard]], the original command pilot, was grounded due to [[M\u00e9ni\u00e8re's disease]].{{sfn|Thompson|2004|p=366}} Making the first crewed flight of the Gemini spacecraft with [[Gus Grissom]] in 1965, Young scored another space first by smuggling a corned beef sandwich onto the spacecraft\u2014a feat for which he was reprimanded. Some members of the US House of Representatives were not pleased about the stunt, claiming that Young cost taxpayers millions of dollars by disrupting a scheduled test of space food during the flight.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://gizmodo.com/50-years-ago-nasa-astronauts-smuggled-a-corned-beef-sa-1693431694 |title=50 Years Ago, NASA Astronauts Smuggled a Corned Beef Sandwich Into Space |work=Gizmodo |last1=Zhang |first1=Sarah |date=March 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/history/mission_trans/GT03_TEC.PDF |title=Composite Air-to-ground and Onboard Voice Tape Transcription of the GT-3 Mission |publisher=National Astronautics and Space Administration |page=45 |date=April 1965 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nYoung then trained as backup pilot for [[Gemini 6A]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/multimedia/imagegallery/image_feature_1010.html |title=Gemini 6 Back-up Crew |publisher=NASA |date=March 23, 2008 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> The assignment of [[Gemini 7]] backup command pilot [[Ed White (astronaut)|Ed White]] to Apollo, created an opening for Young as commander of [[Gemini 10]] in 1966.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MYasNyKQIxMC&pg=PA151&lpg=PA151 |title=Foothold in the Heavens: The Seventies |series=A History of Human Space Exploration |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]] |last1=Evans |first1=Ben |page=151 |date=August 14, 2010 |isbn=978-1-4419-6341-3 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4419-6342-0}}</ref> The mission was the first to perform a rendezvous with two [[Agena target vehicle]]s; and his pilot, [[Michael Collins (astronaut)|Michael Collins]], performed two spacewalks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.space.com/37527-gemini-10-photos.html |title=Gemini 10: NASA's Epic 1st Double Rendezvous Mission in Photos |work=Space.com |last1=Lunsford |first1=Christine |date=September 18, 2017 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1966-066A |title=Gemini 10 |publisher=NASA Space Science Data Coordinated Archive |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Apollo program===\n{{Main|Apollo 10|Apollo 16}}\n[[File:John W. Young on the Moon.jpg|right|thumb|Young jumps while saluting the [[Lunar Flag Assembly|American flag]] during Apollo 16]]\nIn 1966, Young was assigned to an Apollo crew as [[Apollo Command/Service Module|Command Module]] pilot, with Commander [[Thomas P. Stafford|Thomas Stafford]] and [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] pilot [[Eugene Cernan]]. This crew was assigned as backup to the second crewed Apollo mission, planned before the [[Apollo 1]] fire. After that fire, both crews{{clarify|date=March 2019}} were assigned to the first actual crewed mission, [[Apollo 7]], which flew in October 1968.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In May 1969, this crew flew to the Moon on [[Apollo 10]]. While Stafford and Cernan flew the Lunar Module in lunar orbit for the first time, Young flew the Command Module solo. Apollo 10 set the record for the highest speed attained by any crewed vehicle at {{convert|39897|km/h|mph}} during its return to Earth on May 26, 1969.<ref name=\"Guinness2012\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=biWfNzQiR8EC&pg=PA322 |title=Guinness World Records 2012 |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |editor-first=Craig |editor-last=Glenday |page=322 |date=2012 |isbn=978-0-345-53437-8}}</ref><ref name=\"Lloyd2010\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uCgRY6llQpYC&pg=PA280 |title=QI: The Book of General Ignorance |publisher=[[Faber and Faber]] |first1=John |last1=Lloyd |first2=John |last2=Mitchinson |edition=The Noticeably Stouter |page=280 |date=2010 |isbn=978-0-571-27378-2}}</ref>\n\nYoung was backup commander of [[Apollo 13]], the troubled mission in which the Moon landing was aborted because of an explosion in the Service Module.<ref name=\"backup\">{{cite web |url=https://airandspace.si.edu/explore-and-learn/topics/apollo/apollo-program/landing-missions/apollo13-crew.cfm |title=Apollo 13 Crew |publisher=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy rotation, Young became commander of [[Apollo 16]], and studied [[geology]] with his crew while preparing for the mission.<ref name=sudburytraining>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=s-9UAAAAIBAJ&pg=1178,849265&dq=apollo+16+training&hl=en |title=Astronauts training in Ont. |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |newspaper=[[Leader-Post|The Leader-Post]] |location=Regina, Saskatchewan |last=Dickie |first=Allan |date=July 7, 1971 |accessdate=November 26, 2011}}</ref> Apollo 16's lunar landing was almost aborted when a malfunction was detected in the SPS engine control system in the Service Module. It was determined that the problem could be worked around, and the mission continued.<ref name=overview>{{cite web |title=Descartes Surprise |url=http://www.hq.nasa.gov/alsj/a16/a16.summary.html |publisher=Apollo Lunar Surface Journal |accessdate=November 26, 2011}}</ref> On the surface, Young took three moonwalks in the [[Descartes Highlands]] with [[Charles Duke]] on April 21, 22 and 23, 1972, making Young the ninth person to walk on the surface of the Moon, while [[Ken Mattingly]] flew the Command Module in lunar orbit.<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/apollo/missions/apollo16.html |title=Apollo 16 |date=July 8, 2009 |publisher=NASA |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung's final assignment in Apollo was as the backup commander for Cernan on [[Apollo 17]]. The backup crew was originally the [[Apollo 15]] crew, but [[Deke Slayton]] removed them from the assignment when he learned they had taken a small statue to the Moon, as well as stamps that they sold to a dealer.<ref name=15backup>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kAsUAAAAIBAJ&pg=5667,8302&dq=apollo+17+backup+crew&hl=en |title=Apollo crew warned about commercialism |newspaper=The Free Lance-Star |date=August 1, 1972 |accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref name=nasmcrew>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasm.si.edu/collections/imagery/apollo/as17/a17crew.htm |title=Apollo 17 Crew |work=The Apollo Program |publisher=[[National Air and Space Museum]] |location=Washington, D.C. |accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Space Shuttle program===\n{{Main|STS-1|STS-9}}\nIn January 1973 Young was made Chief of the Space Shuttle Branch of the Astronaut Office. In January 1974, he became Chief of the Astronaut Office after the retirement of [[Alan Shepard]].<ref name=\"asf\">{{cite web |url=https://astronautscholarship.org/Astronauts/john-w-young/ |title=John Young |publisher=Astronaut Scholarship Foundation |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung flew two missions of the Space Shuttle, both aboard the {{OV|Columbia}}. He commanded the program's 1981 maiden orbital flight, [[STS-1]], and in 1983 commanded [[STS-9]], which carried the first [[Spacelab]] module.<ref name=\"asf\" /> In 1986 he was in line to make a record seventh space flight on [[Canceled Space Shuttle missions#Canceled due to the Challenger disaster|STS-61-J]] to deploy the [[Hubble Space Telescope]], but the [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|Space Shuttle ''Challenger'' disaster]] earlier that year had delayed NASA's schedule.<ref name=\"sts61\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astronautix.com/flights/sts61j.htm |title=STS-61-J |publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica |date=November 17, 2007 |accessdate=March 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108041720/http://astronautix.com/flights/sts61j.htm |archivedate=January 8, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nYoung was openly critical of NASA management following the ''Challenger'' disaster,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory/nasa-legendary-astronaut-moonwalker-john-young-died-52180080 |title=NASA: Legendary astronaut, moonwalker John Young has died |last1=Dunn |first1=Marcia |publisher=ABC News |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106202306/http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory/nasa-legendary-astronaut-moonwalker-john-young-died-52180080 |archive-date=January 6, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and in April 1987 was made Special Assistant to JSC Director [[Aaron Cohen (Deputy NASA administrator)|Aaron Cohen]] for Engineering, Operations and Safety.<ref name=\"bio\" /> NASA denied that his criticism triggered the move, although Young and industry insiders believed that was the reason for the reassignment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-16/news/mn-711_1_johnson-space-center-in-houston |title=The Nation |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 16, 1987 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-07-30/news/mn-378_1_shuttle-flight |title=Top Astronaut Says NASA Forced Him From Job |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 30, 1987 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In February 1996, he was assigned as Associate Director (Technical) JSC.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nDuring his NASA career, Young logged more than 15,000 hours of training, mostly in simulators, to prepare for positions on eleven spaceflights in prime and backup crew positions.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\n===Retirement===\n[[File:John Young 2006.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Young at the 25th anniversary of STS-1 at [[Kennedy Space Center]]]]\nYoung worked for NASA for 42 years and announced his retirement on December 7, 2004. He retired on December 31, 2004, at the age of 74, but continued to attend the Monday Morning Meeting at the Astronaut Office at JSC for several years thereafter.<ref name=\"Fuglesang\">{{Cite book |title=Tretton dygn i rymden efter fjorton \u00e5r p\u00e5 jorden: dagbok fr\u00e5n rymden |trans-title=Thirteen days in space, after fourteen years on earth: a diary from space |language=Swedish |publisher=Albert Bonniers F\u00f6rlag |first=Christer |last=Fuglesang |date=2007 |isbn=978-91-85555-15-4 |oclc=185242561}}</ref> He logged more than 15,275 hours flying time in [[Powered aircraft#Propeller aircraft|props]], [[Jet aircraft|jets]], [[helicopter]]s, and [[Rocket-powered aircraft|rocket jets]]; more than 9,200 hours in [[Northrop T-38 Talon|T-38]]s; and 835 hours in [[spacecraft]] during six space flights.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nOn April 12, 2006, Young appeared at the 25th anniversary of the STS-1 launch at the [[Kennedy Space Center Visitor Complex]], along with pilot [[Robert Crippen]]. The two spoke of their experiences during the flight.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mediaarchive.ksc.nasa.gov/detail.cfm?mediaid=28394 |title=To honor the 25th anniversary ... |publisher=NASA |first=Jeanne |last=Ryba |date=April 7, 2006 |access-date=October 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531211821/http://mediaarchive.ksc.nasa.gov/detail.cfm?mediaid=28394 |archivedate=May 31, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Young published an autobiography, ''Forever Young''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.upf.com/book.asp?id=YOUNG001 |title=Forever Young: A Life of Adventure in Air and Space |work=University Press of Florida |access-date=May 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYoung married Barbara White of [[Savannah, Georgia]], and they had two children, Sandra and John.<ref name=\"fw4465\" /> They were divorced in 1972 after 16 years of marriage.<ref name=\"telegraph19810411\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gKgrAAAAIBAJ&pg=5388%2C2658262 |title=Young: America's old man of space |work=[[Nashua Telegraph]] |agency=Associated Press |volume=113 |issue=36 |page=23 |date=April 11, 1981}}</ref> He later married Susy Feldman,<ref name=\"telegraph19810411\" /> and lived in [[El Lago, Texas]], a suburb of Houston.\n\nYoung died on January 5, 2018, at his home in Houston of complications from [[pneumonia]]. He was 87.<ref name=\"nyt20180106\"/><ref name=\"nasa20180106\">{{cite web |title=NASA Remembers Agency's Most Experienced Astronaut |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-remembers-agency-s-most-experienced-astronaut |publisher=NASA |date=January 6, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106201553/https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-remembers-agency-s-most-experienced-astronaut/ |archivedate=January 6, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"collect20180106\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.collectspace.com/news/news-010618a-astronaut-john-young-obituary.html |title=John Young, ninth astronaut on moon, led first shuttle mission, dies at 87 |work=[[collectSPACE]] |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n===Military and NASA insignia and decorations===\n* [[China Service Medal]] (1953)\n* [[Korean Service Medal]] with two [[battle stars]] (1953)\n* [[National Defense Service Medal]] with star (1953, 1966)\n* [[United Nations Korea Medal]] (1953)\n* [[Astronaut badge#U.S. Navy, Marine Corps, and Coast Guard astronauts|Navy Astronaut Wings]] (1965)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\">{{cite web |url=https://searchpub.nssc.nasa.gov/servlet/sm.web.Fetch/Agency_Awards_Historical_Recipient_List.pdf?rhid=1000&did=2120817&type=released |title=Historical Recipient List |publisher=NASA |accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Distinguished Service Medal (United States Navy)|Navy Distinguished Service Medal]] with [[5/16 inch star|gold award star]] (1969, 1972)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] with two gold award stars<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Congressional Space Medal of Honor]] (1981)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Distinguished Service Medal]] (1969) with three [[oak leaf cluster]]s (1981, 2004)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Achievement Medal]] (1994)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Engineering Achievement Medal]] (1988)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Service Medal]] (1965, 1966, 2006)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.com/bio/award-esm.htm |title=Biography: 2 Exceptional Service Medals |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[NASA Outstanding Leadership Medal]] (1992)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Space Flight Medal]] (1981, 1983)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n\n==Awards and honors==\n[[File:20-02-001-aviation.jpg|thumb|right|Plaque of Young at the [[Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame]]]]\n\n* Inducted into six Aviation and Astronaut Halls of Fame<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* General [[James E. Hill]] Lifetime Space Achievement Award<ref>{{cite web |url=http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/node/580.html |title=The General James E. Hill Lifetime Space Achievement Award |publisher=National Space Symposium |date=2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615164321/http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/node/580.html |archivedate=June 15, 2013 }}</ref> from the [[Space Foundation]] (2010)<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/media/press-releases/legendary-astronaut-john-young-to-receive-general-james-e-hill-lifetime-space-a.html |title=Legendary Astronaut John Young to Receive General James E. Hill Lifetime Space Achievement Award |publisher=National Space Symposium |first=Janet |last=Stevens |date=January 22, 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615164322/http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/media/press-releases/legendary-astronaut-john-young-to-receive-general-james-e-hill-lifetime-space-a.html |archivedate=June 15, 2013 }}</ref>\n* Exceptional Engineering Achievement Award (1985)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Academy of Achievement|Golden Plate Award]] for Science and Exploration (1993)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.achievement.org/our-history/golden-plate-awards/all-honorees/ |title=Golden Plate Awardees listed by year |publisher=Academy of Achievement |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[American Astronautical Society]] Space Flight Award (1993)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n*In 1995, Young was inducted into the [[International Air & Space Hall of Fame]] at the [[San Diego Air & Space Museum]].<ref>Sprekelmeyer, Linda, editor. ''These We Honor: The International Aerospace Hall of Fame''. Donning Co. Publishers, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-57864-397-4}}.</ref>\n*In 2001, Young was inducted into the [[Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Captain John W. Young |url=http://www.gaaviationhalloffame.com/Hall-of-Fame.48.0.html?avid=93 |access-date=October 9, 2018 |website=Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame}}</ref>\n* NASA Ambassador of Exploration (2005)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/centers/johnson/news/releases/H05-192.html |title=NASA Names Astronaut John Young Ambassador of Exploration |publisher=NASA |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* He was the first John Young History Maker Honoree in 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cflhistory.org/cflhistory.org/wp-content/uploads/2017-John-Young-History-Maker-Sponsorship-Package.pdf |title=11th Annual John Young History Maker Celebration |publisher=Historical Society of Central Florida |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* Six [[Honorary degree|honorary]] doctorate degrees<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Florida State Road 423|John Young Parkway]], a major highway in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] and [[Kissimmee, Florida]], is named for him. When he heard the highway was named for him, he said \"Them boys shouldn't a'done that. I ain't dead yet\".<ref name=\"sts61\" /> An elementary school ([[Orange County Public Schools|OCPS]]) on the parkway also bears his name.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://johnyounges.ocps.net/ |title=John Young Elementary School Homepage |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=John Young Elementary School}}</ref>\n* The planetarium at the [[Orlando Science Center]] was originally named in his honor.<ref name=\"orsent19901028\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1990-10-28/news/9010240091_1_telescope-science-center-planets |title=Where Stargazers Can Get The Big Picture |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |first=Cindy |last=Schreuder |date=October 28, 1990 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n*Ranked as the No. 3 most-popular space hero in a 2010 [[Space Foundation]] survey<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.spacefoundation.org/news/space-foundation-survey-reveals-broad-range-space-heroes-early-astronauts-still-most |title=Space Foundation Survey Reveals Broad Range of Space Heroes; Early Astronauts Still the Most Inspirational |publisher=Space Foundation |first=Carol |last=Hively |date=October 27, 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107174826/https://www.spacefoundation.org/news/space-foundation-survey-reveals-broad-range-space-heroes-early-astronauts-still-most |archive-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Recipient of ''[[Aviation Week]]''{{'}}s 1998 [[Philip J. Klass]] Award for Lifetime Achievement<ref>{{cite web |url=https://laureates.aviationweek.com/en/winners/previous-winners.html |title=Aviation Week's Laureate Awards Past Winners |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=Aviation Week}}</ref>\n* Asteroid [[5362 Johnyoung]] was named in his memory in 2018\n\nAlong with nine other Gemini astronauts, Young was inducted into the [[International Space Hall of Fame]] in 1982.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28841417/albuquerque_journal/ |title=Astronauts Laud Gemini as Precursor to Shuttle |last1=Shay |first1=Erin |newspaper=Albuquerque Journal |location=Albuquerque, New Mexico |date=October 3, 1982 |page=3 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Young, along with the other 12 Gemini astronauts, was inducted into the second [[U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame]] class in 1993.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33582881/florida_today/ |title=Activities Honor Gemini Astronauts |newspaper=Florida Today |location=Cocoa, Florida |date=March 14, 1993 |page=41 |via=Newspapers.com |last1=Clark |first1=Amy}}</ref>\n\n===Organizations===\n* [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]] [[fellow]]<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.com/bio/org.htm |title=Biography: Organization Memberships |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* American Astronautical Society fellow<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\" /><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]] fellow<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\" /><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Tau Beta Pi]] Engineering Honor Society member<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tbp.org/about/Dist/Astronauts.cfm |title=Astronauts and Scientists |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=Tau Beta Pi}}</ref>\n* [[Sigma Gamma Tau]] Aerospace Engineering Honor Society member<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* Georgia Tech [[ANAK Society]] member<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kp5sCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=georgia+tech+anak+society+john+young&source=bl&ots=xmFrxa_pFd&sig=iqN7YnTgt_4jKESg5JfKT9eC0RQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjji5297cTYAhWGvVMKHXLKDCkQ6AEIPzAD#v=onepage&q=georgia%20tech%20anak%20society%20john%20young&f=false |title=Secret Societies Vol. 3: The Collegiate Secret Societies of America |last1=Francis |first1=Arthur Morius |page=26 |chapter=2 |publisher=Lulu.com |date=February 20, 2015 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}{{self-published source}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n* [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity member<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sigmachi.org/the-sigma-chi-museum |publisher=Sigma Chi Fraternity |title=The Sigma Chi Museum |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, [[Northrop Grumman]] announced that the [[Cygnus spacecraft]] for their tenth cargo resupply mission to the [[International Space Station]] would be named S.S. ''John Young''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.space.com/42250-cygnus-cargo-ship-apollo-john-young.html |title=Space Station-Bound Cargo Ship Named for Moonwalker John Young |work=Space.com |last=Pearlman |first=Robert Z. |date=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Florida State Road 423]] is named in his honor, as is [[Orange County Public Schools|John Young Elementary School]] in Orlando, Florida.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volz |first1=Brianna |title=Astronaut John Young, who grew up in Orlando, dies at 87 |url=https://www.clickorlando.com/news/space-news/astronaut-john-young-dies-at-87 |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |work=WKMG |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Scott Kelly (astronaut) | Scott Kelly]] (an American astronaut who [[ISS year long mission | spent nearly a year aboard the International Space Station]]) had high praise for Young in his memoir, ''[[Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery]]''. Upon learning that Young would interview him as part of his astronaut selection process, Kelly listed some of Young's more impressive achievements, and then stated simply, \"He was what you might call an astronaut's astronaut, a living legend. I wanted to be just like him.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Kelly |first=Scott |others=With Margaret Lazarus Dean |title=Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery |title-link=Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf, a division of Penguin Random House |year=2017 |page=201 |isbn=9781524731595}}</ref>\n\n==In media==\nIn the 1995 film ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]'', Young was played by Ben Marley.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0112384/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=Apollo 13, Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> In the 1998 [[HBO]] [[miniseries]], ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'', he was played by [[John Posey (actor)|John Posey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120570/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=From the Earth to the Moon, Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYoung is one of the astronauts featured in the 2007 documentary film and book ''[[In the Shadow of the Moon (2007 film)|In the Shadow of the Moon]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0925248/fullcredits#cast |title=In the Shadow of the Moon: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> the 2007 documentary film ''[[The Wonder of It All (2007 film)|The Wonder of It All]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0928406/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=The Wonder of It All: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> and the 2008 Discovery Channel series ''[[When We Left Earth: The NASA Missions|When We Left Earth]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1233514/fullcredits |title=When We Left Earth: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung's voice during the STS-1 mission can be heard in the song \"[[Countdown (Rush song)|Countdown]]\" by [[Rush (band)|Rush]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Spaceflight}}\n*[[List of spaceflight records]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Neal |authorlink=Neal Thompson |title=Light This Candle: The Life & Times of Alan Shepard, America's First Spaceman |edition=1st |date=2004 |publisher=Crown Publishers |location=New York |isbn=0-609-61001-5 |oclc=52631310 |lccn=2003015688 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lightthiscandlel00thom }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Conversation-With-John-Young-1563092.php \"Conversation With John Young\"], ''Houston Chronicle'' (December 17, 2004)\n*[http://www.balettie.com/young/ \"The Big Picture: Ways to Mitigate or Prevent Very Bad Planet Earth Events\"], an essay by Young\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{C-SPAN|johnyoung04}}\n*{{IMDb name|0974135}}\n*{{Find a Grave|186428895}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Alan Shepard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief of the Astronaut Office]]\n|years=1974\u20131987}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Daniel Brandenstein]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{People who have traveled to the Moon}}\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 2}}\n{{Gemini program}}\n{{Congressional Space Medal of Honor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, John}}\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:John Young| ]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:1965 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1966 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1969 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1972 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1981 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1983 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Apollo 10]]\n[[Category:Apollo 16]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:Aviators from California]]\n[[Category:Apollo program astronauts]]\n[[Category:People who have walked on the Moon]]\n[[Category:American aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:United States Navy astronauts]]\n[[Category:NASA civilian astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Astronaut Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Test Pilot School alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n[[Category:National Aviation Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:American test pilots]]\n[[Category:NASA people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Congressional Space Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Exceptional Achievement Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Exceptional Service Medal]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Toastmasters members]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Florida]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Orlando, Florida]]\n[[Category:Project Gemini astronauts]]\n[[Category:Space Shuttle program astronauts]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Watts Young\n| image         = Astronaut John W. Young.jpg\n| caption       =\n| nationality   = American\n| birth_name    = John Watts Young\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1930|09|24}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2018|01|05|1930|09|24}}\n| death_place   = [[Seabrook, Texas]] U.S.\n| occupation    = [[United States Naval Aviator|Naval Aviator]], [[test pilot]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]], B.S. 1952\n| module        = {{Infobox astronaut|child =yes\n| type          = [[NASA]] astronaut\n| rank          = {{Dodseal|USNO6|25}} [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]], [[United States Navy|USN]]\n| selection     = [[List of astronauts by year of selection#1962|1962 NASA Group 2]]\n| time          = 34d 19h 39m\n| eva1          = 3\n| eva2          = 20h 14m 14s\n| mission       = [[Gemini 3]], [[Gemini 10]], [[Apollo 10]], [[Apollo 16]], [[STS-1]], [[STS-9]]\n| insignia      = [[File:Gemini3.png|45px]] [[File:Gemini 10 Insignia.svg|54px]] [[File:Apollo-10-LOGO.png|45px]] [[File:Apollo-16-LOGO.png|45px]] [[File:Sts-1-patch.png|45px]] [[File:Sts-9-patch.png|45px]]\n| Date of ret   = December 31, 2004\n| awards        = [[File:Dfc-usa.jpg|20px|link=Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]] {{CS Medal of Honor}} [[File:NASA Distinguished Service Medal.jpg|20px|link=NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n}}}}\n\n'''John Watts Young''' (September 24, 1930&nbsp;\u2013 January 5, 2018) was an American [[astronaut]], [[United States Navy|naval officer]] and [[United States Naval Aviator|aviator]], [[test pilot]], and [[aerospace engineering|aeronautical engineer]]. He became the [[List of Apollo astronauts#People who have walked on the Moon|ninth person to walk on the Moon]] as Commander of the [[Apollo 16]] mission in 1972. Young enjoyed the longest career of any astronaut, becoming the first person to fly six space missions over the course of 42 years of active [[NASA]] service.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/young.html |title=Biographical Data: John W. Young (Captain, USN Ret.) |publisher=NASA |date=August 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref> He is the only person to have piloted and commanded four different classes of spacecraft: [[Project Gemini|Gemini]], the [[Apollo Command and Service Module]], the [[Apollo Lunar Module]], and the [[Space Shuttle]].<ref name=\"sentinel20160924\">{{cite news |last1=Speck |first1=Emilee |title=Moon-walking astronaut John Young turned 86 on Saturday |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/space/go-for-launch/os-nasa-astronaut-john-young-turns-86-20160923-story.html |access-date=August 16, 2017 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=September 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965 Young flew on the [[Gemini 3|first crewed Gemini mission]], and then commanded the 1966 [[Gemini 10]] mission. In 1969 during [[Apollo 10]], he became the first person to fly solo around the Moon.<ref name=\"nasa200412007\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/vision/space/features/young_retires.html |title=From Gemini to Shuttle: John Young Retires |publisher=NASA |date=December 7, 2004 |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He then walked on the Moon and drove the [[Lunar Roving Vehicle]] on the Moon's surface during [[Apollo 16]], and is one of only three people to have [[List of Apollo astronauts|flown to the Moon]] twice.<ref name=\"npr20180106\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/01/16/505928876/gene-cernan-last-man-to-walk-on-the-moon-dies-at-82 |title=Gene Cernan, Last Man To Walk On The Moon, Dies At 82 |publisher=NPR |last1=Lewis |first1=Russell |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> \n\nYoung also commanded two flights of [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']]: [[STS-1]] in 1981, the [[Space Shuttle]] program's first launch, and [[STS-9]] in 1983. Young served as [[Chief of the Astronaut Office]] from 1974 to 1987, and retired from NASA in 2004.\n\n==Early years and education==\nYoung was born in [[San Francisco, California]], on September 24, 1930,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28981374/the_orlando_sentinel/ |title=Astronauts Could Have a Party |newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel |location=Orlando, Florida |date=February 3, 1963 |page=15 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> to parents William Hugh Young, a civil engineer,<ref name=\"nyt20180106\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/06/obituaries/john-young-dead.html |title=John Young, Who Led First Space Shuttle Mission, Dies at 87 |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Richard |last=Goldstein |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> and Wanda Howland Young.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\">{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/biographies-list/bios-y/Young-John/Young-John-Text.html |title=John Watts Young |publisher=Navy Office of Information, Biographies Branch |date=April 10, 1972}}</ref> At 18 months old, due to the [[Great Depression]], he moved with his family to [[Cartersville, Georgia|Cartersville]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]],<ref name=\"fortune20180106\">{{cite news |url=http://amp.timeinc.net/fortune/2018/01/06/astronaut-john-young-dead |title=Astronaut John Young, One of Only 12 to Walk on Moon, Dies at 87 |work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |agency=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> then to [[Orlando, Florida]], where he attended grade school and later [[Orange County Public Schools#High schools|Orlando High School]] until graduating in 1948.<ref name=\"sjg19650324\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HhpdAAAAIBAJ&pg=1598%2C4411712 |title=John Young, as Early as 1946, Displayed Interest in Rockets |work=[[St. Joseph Gazette]] |agency=Associated Press |volume=120 |issue=238 |page=6A |date=March 24, 1965 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"jwy-edu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/education.htm |title=Biography: Education |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128151906/http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/education.htm |archive-date=November 28, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Young was a [[Scouts BSA (Boy Scouts of America)|Boy Scout]] and earned the rank of [[Second Class (Boy Scouts of America)|Second Class]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scouting.org/About/FactSheets/scouting_space.aspx |title=Scouting and Space Exploration |website=Scouting.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303213130/http://www.scouting.org/about/factsheets/scouting_space.aspx |archivedate=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nYoung earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree with highest honors in [[Aerospace engineering|Aeronautical Engineering]] from the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] in 1952; while attending, he became a member of the national military honor society [[Scabbard and Blade]] and [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity.<ref name=\"fw4465\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1774&dat=19650404&id=AZscAAAAIBAJ&pg=5001,1212947 |title=Virgil Grissom and John Young: Our Trail-Blazing \"Twin\" Astronauts |work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]] |series=Family Weekly |first=John W. |last=Wasik |page=4 |date=April 4, 1965 |access-date=January 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"blueprint1952\">{{cite book |url=http://hdl.handle.net/1853/25833 |title=Blue Print |publisher=[[Georgia Institute of Technology]] |editor-first=Blount |editor-last=Boswell |volume=45 |page=108 |date=1952}}</ref>\n\n==Navy service==\n{{quote box|align=right|width=28%|quote=I got a telegram from the [[Chief of Naval Operations]] asking me not to do this anymore.|salign=right|source=\u2014Young, describing an air-to-air missile test in which he and another pilot approached each other at Mach 3 - risking destruction of both aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/navycareer.htm |title=Astronaut John W. Young - Navy Career |website=Johnwyoung.org}}</ref>}}\n\nAfter graduating from [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]] in 1952, Young entered the [[United States Navy]] through the [[Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps|Navy ROTC]] and was commissioned on June 6, 1952, as an [[ensign (rank)|ensign]].<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> He served as fire control officer on the destroyer {{USS|Laws|DD-558|6}} until June 1953 and completed a tour in the [[Sea of Japan]] during the [[Korean War]]. Following this assignment, he was sent to flight training. In January 1954, he was designated a Navy helicopter pilot.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> After receiving his [[United States Naval Aviator|aviator wings]] on December 20, 1954, he was assigned to Fighter Squadron 103 ([[VFA-103|VF-103]]) for four years, flying [[Grumman F9F Cougar]]s from {{USS|Coral Sea|CV-43|6}} and [[Vought F8U Crusader]]s from {{USS|Forrestal|CV-59|6}}.<ref name=\"nmmuseum\" />\n\nAfter training at the [[United States Naval Test Pilot School]] in 1959 with the Class 23, Young was assigned to the Naval Air Test Center at [[Naval Air Station Patuxent River]], Maryland, for three years. His test projects included evaluations of the [[Vought XF8U-3 Crusader III|XF8U-3 Crusader III]] and [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4 Phantom II]] fighter weapons systems. In 1962, he set two world time-to-climb records while flying his Phantom II, attaining {{convert|3000|m|ft|0|sp=us}} from a standing start in 34.52 seconds and {{convert|25000|m|ft|0|sp=us}} from a standing start in 227.6 seconds.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> He also served as maintenance officer of Fighter Squadron 143 ([[VFA-143|VF-143]]) from April to September 1962.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nFellow astronaut [[Charles Bolden]] described Young and [[Robert L. Gibson|Robert \"Hoot\" Gibson]] as the two best pilots he had met during his aviation career: \"Never met two people like them. Everyone else gets into an airplane; John and Hoot wear their airplane. They're just awesome\".<ref name=\"bolden20040106\">{{cite interview |title=Charles F. Bolden |date=January 6, 2004 |access-date=January 6, 2014 |last=Bolden |first=Charles F. |subjectlink=Charles Bolden |interviewer1=Johnson, Sandra |interviewer2=Wright, Rebecca |interviewer3=Ross-Nazzal, Jennifer |work=NASA Johnson Space Center Oral History Project |location=Houston, Texas |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/history/oral_histories/BoldenCF/BoldenCF_1-6-04.htm}}</ref> Young retired from the Navy as a [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] in September 1976, after 25 years.<ref name=\"nmmuseum\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nmspacemuseum.org/halloffame/detail.php?id=70 |title=Commanded the first shuttle flight, the first person to enter space six times |publisher=New Mexico Museum of Space History |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==NASA career==\n===Project Gemini===\n{{Main|Gemini 3|Gemini 10}}\n[[File:Astronaut John Young gemini 3.jpg|left|thumb|Young, age 34, as pilot of Gemini 3]]\nJoining [[NASA]] in 1962, Young was the first of the [[NASA Astronaut Group 2|Astronaut Group 2]] to fly in space, replacing [[Thomas P. Stafford]] as pilot of [[Gemini 3]] when [[Alan Shepard]], the original command pilot, was grounded due to [[M\u00e9ni\u00e8re's disease]].{{sfn|Thompson|2004|p=366}} Making the first crewed flight of the Gemini spacecraft with [[Gus Grissom]] in 1965, Young scored another space first by smuggling a corned beef sandwich onto the spacecraft\u2014a feat for which he was reprimanded. Some members of the US House of Representatives were not pleased about the stunt, claiming that Young cost taxpayers millions of dollars by disrupting a scheduled test of space food during the flight.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://gizmodo.com/50-years-ago-nasa-astronauts-smuggled-a-corned-beef-sa-1693431694 |title=50 Years Ago, NASA Astronauts Smuggled a Corned Beef Sandwich Into Space |work=Gizmodo |last1=Zhang |first1=Sarah |date=March 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/history/mission_trans/GT03_TEC.PDF |title=Composite Air-to-ground and Onboard Voice Tape Transcription of the GT-3 Mission |publisher=National Astronautics and Space Administration |page=45 |date=April 1965 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nYoung then trained as backup pilot for [[Gemini 6A]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/multimedia/imagegallery/image_feature_1010.html |title=Gemini 6 Back-up Crew |publisher=NASA |date=March 23, 2008 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> The assignment of [[Gemini 7]] backup command pilot [[Ed White (astronaut)|Ed White]] to Apollo, created an opening for Young as commander of [[Gemini 10]] in 1966.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MYasNyKQIxMC&pg=PA151&lpg=PA151 |title=Foothold in the Heavens: The Seventies |series=A History of Human Space Exploration |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]] |last1=Evans |first1=Ben |page=151 |date=August 14, 2010 |isbn=978-1-4419-6341-3 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4419-6342-0}}</ref> The mission was the first to perform a rendezvous with two [[Agena target vehicle]]s; and his pilot, [[Michael Collins (astronaut)|Michael Collins]], performed two spacewalks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.space.com/37527-gemini-10-photos.html |title=Gemini 10: NASA's Epic 1st Double Rendezvous Mission in Photos |work=Space.com |last1=Lunsford |first1=Christine |date=September 18, 2017 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1966-066A |title=Gemini 10 |publisher=NASA Space Science Data Coordinated Archive |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Apollo program===\n{{Main|Apollo 10|Apollo 16}}\n[[File:John W. Young on the Moon.jpg|right|thumb|Young jumps while saluting the [[Lunar Flag Assembly|American flag]] during Apollo 16]]\nIn 1966, Young was assigned to an Apollo crew as [[Apollo Command/Service Module|Command Module]] pilot, with Commander [[Thomas P. Stafford|Thomas Stafford]] and [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] pilot [[Eugene Cernan]]. This crew was assigned as backup to the second crewed Apollo mission, planned before the [[Apollo 1]] fire. After that fire, both crews{{clarify|date=March 2019}} were assigned to the first actual crewed mission, [[Apollo 7]], which flew in October 1968.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In May 1969, this crew flew to the Moon on [[Apollo 10]]. While Stafford and Cernan flew the Lunar Module in lunar orbit for the first time, Young flew the Command Module solo. Apollo 10 set the record for the highest speed attained by any crewed vehicle at {{convert|39897|km/h|mph}} during its return to Earth on May 26, 1969.<ref name=\"Guinness2012\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=biWfNzQiR8EC&pg=PA322 |title=Guinness World Records 2012 |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |editor-first=Craig |editor-last=Glenday |page=322 |date=2012 |isbn=978-0-345-53437-8}}</ref><ref name=\"Lloyd2010\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uCgRY6llQpYC&pg=PA280 |title=QI: The Book of General Ignorance |publisher=[[Faber and Faber]] |first1=John |last1=Lloyd |first2=John |last2=Mitchinson |edition=The Noticeably Stouter |page=280 |date=2010 |isbn=978-0-571-27378-2}}</ref>\n\nYoung was backup commander of [[Apollo 13]], the troubled mission in which the Moon landing was aborted because of an explosion in the Service Module.<ref name=\"backup\">{{cite web |url=https://airandspace.si.edu/explore-and-learn/topics/apollo/apollo-program/landing-missions/apollo13-crew.cfm |title=Apollo 13 Crew |publisher=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy rotation, Young became commander of [[Apollo 16]], and studied [[geology]] with his crew while preparing for the mission.<ref name=sudburytraining>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=s-9UAAAAIBAJ&pg=1178,849265&dq=apollo+16+training&hl=en |title=Astronauts training in Ont. |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |newspaper=[[Leader-Post|The Leader-Post]] |location=Regina, Saskatchewan |last=Dickie |first=Allan |date=July 7, 1971 |accessdate=November 26, 2011}}</ref> Apollo 16's lunar landing was almost aborted when a malfunction was detected in the SPS engine control system in the Service Module. It was determined that the problem could be worked around, and the mission continued.<ref name=overview>{{cite web |title=Descartes Surprise |url=http://www.hq.nasa.gov/alsj/a16/a16.summary.html |publisher=Apollo Lunar Surface Journal |accessdate=November 26, 2011}}</ref> On the surface, Young took three moonwalks in the [[Descartes Highlands]] with [[Charles Duke]] on April 21, 22 and 23, 1972, making Young the ninth person to walk on the surface of the Moon, while [[Ken Mattingly]] flew the Command Module in lunar orbit.<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/apollo/missions/apollo16.html |title=Apollo 16 |date=July 8, 2009 |publisher=NASA |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung's final assignment in Apollo was as the backup commander for Cernan on [[Apollo 17]]. The backup crew was originally the [[Apollo 15]] crew, but [[Deke Slayton]] removed them from the assignment when he learned they had taken a small statue to the Moon, as well as stamps that they sold to a dealer.<ref name=15backup>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kAsUAAAAIBAJ&pg=5667,8302&dq=apollo+17+backup+crew&hl=en |title=Apollo crew warned about commercialism |newspaper=The Free Lance-Star |date=August 1, 1972 |accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref name=nasmcrew>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasm.si.edu/collections/imagery/apollo/as17/a17crew.htm |title=Apollo 17 Crew |work=The Apollo Program |publisher=[[National Air and Space Museum]] |location=Washington, D.C. |accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Space Shuttle program===\n{{Main|STS-1|STS-9}}\nIn January 1973 Young was made Chief of the Space Shuttle Branch of the Astronaut Office. In January 1974, he became Chief of the Astronaut Office after the retirement of [[Alan Shepard]].<ref name=\"asf\">{{cite web |url=https://astronautscholarship.org/Astronauts/john-w-young/ |title=John Young |publisher=Astronaut Scholarship Foundation |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung flew two missions of the Space Shuttle, both aboard the {{OV|Columbia}}. He commanded the program's 1981 maiden orbital flight, [[STS-1]], and in 1983 commanded [[STS-9]], which carried the first [[Spacelab]] module.<ref name=\"asf\" /> In 1986 he was in line to make a record seventh space flight on [[Canceled Space Shuttle missions#Canceled due to the Challenger disaster|STS-61-J]] to deploy the [[Hubble Space Telescope]], but the [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|Space Shuttle ''Challenger'' disaster]] earlier that year had delayed NASA's schedule.<ref name=\"sts61\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astronautix.com/flights/sts61j.htm |title=STS-61-J |publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica |date=November 17, 2007 |accessdate=March 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108041720/http://astronautix.com/flights/sts61j.htm |archivedate=January 8, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nYoung was openly critical of NASA management following the ''Challenger'' disaster,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory/nasa-legendary-astronaut-moonwalker-john-young-died-52180080 |title=NASA: Legendary astronaut, moonwalker John Young has died |last1=Dunn |first1=Marcia |publisher=ABC News |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106202306/http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory/nasa-legendary-astronaut-moonwalker-john-young-died-52180080 |archive-date=January 6, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and in April 1987 was made Special Assistant to JSC Director [[Aaron Cohen (Deputy NASA administrator)|Aaron Cohen]] for Engineering, Operations and Safety.<ref name=\"bio\" /> NASA denied that his criticism triggered the move, although Young and industry insiders believed that was the reason for the reassignment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-16/news/mn-711_1_johnson-space-center-in-houston |title=The Nation |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 16, 1987 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-07-30/news/mn-378_1_shuttle-flight |title=Top Astronaut Says NASA Forced Him From Job |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 30, 1987 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In February 1996, he was assigned as Associate Director (Technical) JSC.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nDuring his NASA career, Young logged more than 15,000 hours of training, mostly in simulators, to prepare for positions on eleven spaceflights in prime and backup crew positions.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\n===Retirement===\n[[File:John Young 2006.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Young at the 25th anniversary of STS-1 at [[Kennedy Space Center]]]]\nYoung worked for NASA for 42 years and announced his retirement on December 7, 2004. He retired on December 31, 2004, at the age of 74, but continued to attend the Monday Morning Meeting at the Astronaut Office at JSC for several years thereafter.<ref name=\"Fuglesang\">{{Cite book |title=Tretton dygn i rymden efter fjorton \u00e5r p\u00e5 jorden: dagbok fr\u00e5n rymden |trans-title=Thirteen days in space, after fourteen years on earth: a diary from space |language=Swedish |publisher=Albert Bonniers F\u00f6rlag |first=Christer |last=Fuglesang |date=2007 |isbn=978-91-85555-15-4 |oclc=185242561}}</ref> He logged more than 15,275 hours flying time in [[Powered aircraft#Propeller aircraft|props]], [[Jet aircraft|jets]], [[helicopter]]s, and [[Rocket-powered aircraft|rocket jets]]; more than 9,200 hours in [[Northrop T-38 Talon|T-38]]s; and 835 hours in [[spacecraft]] during six space flights.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nOn April 12, 2006, Young appeared at the 25th anniversary of the STS-1 launch at the [[Kennedy Space Center Visitor Complex]], along with pilot [[Robert Crippen]]. The two spoke of their experiences during the flight.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mediaarchive.ksc.nasa.gov/detail.cfm?mediaid=28394 |title=To honor the 25th anniversary ... |publisher=NASA |first=Jeanne |last=Ryba |date=April 7, 2006 |access-date=October 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531211821/http://mediaarchive.ksc.nasa.gov/detail.cfm?mediaid=28394 |archivedate=May 31, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Young published an autobiography, ''Forever Young''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.upf.com/book.asp?id=YOUNG001 |title=Forever Young: A Life of Adventure in Air and Space |work=University Press of Florida |access-date=May 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYoung married Barbara White of [[Savannah, Georgia]], and they had two children, Sandra and John.<ref name=\"fw4465\" /> They were divorced in 1972 after 16 years of marriage.<ref name=\"telegraph19810411\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gKgrAAAAIBAJ&pg=5388%2C2658262 |title=Young: America's old man of space |work=[[Nashua Telegraph]] |agency=Associated Press |volume=113 |issue=36 |page=23 |date=April 11, 1981}}</ref> He later married Susy Feldman,<ref name=\"telegraph19810411\" /> and lived in [[El Lago, Texas]], a suburb of Houston.\n\nYoung died on January 5, 2018, at his home in Houston of complications from [[pneumonia]]. He was 87.<ref name=\"nyt20180106\"/><ref name=\"nasa20180106\">{{cite web |title=NASA Remembers Agency's Most Experienced Astronaut |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-remembers-agency-s-most-experienced-astronaut |publisher=NASA |date=January 6, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106201553/https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-remembers-agency-s-most-experienced-astronaut/ |archivedate=January 6, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"collect20180106\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.collectspace.com/news/news-010618a-astronaut-john-young-obituary.html |title=John Young, ninth astronaut on moon, led first shuttle mission, dies at 87 |work=[[collectSPACE]] |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n\n==Recognition==\n===Military and NASA insignia and decorations===\n* [[China Service Medal]] (1953)\n* [[Korean Service Medal]] with two [[battle stars]] (1953)\n* [[National Defense Service Medal]] with star (1953, 1966)\n* [[United Nations Korea Medal]] (1953)\n* [[Astronaut badge#U.S. Navy, Marine Corps, and Coast Guard astronauts|Navy Astronaut Wings]] (1965)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\">{{cite web |url=https://searchpub.nssc.nasa.gov/servlet/sm.web.Fetch/Agency_Awards_Historical_Recipient_List.pdf?rhid=1000&did=2120817&type=released |title=Historical Recipient List |publisher=NASA |accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Distinguished Service Medal (United States Navy)|Navy Distinguished Service Medal]] with [[5/16 inch star|gold award star]] (1969, 1972)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] with two gold award stars<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Congressional Space Medal of Honor]] (1981)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Distinguished Service Medal]] (1969) with three [[oak leaf cluster]]s (1981, 2004)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Achievement Medal]] (1994)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Engineering Achievement Medal]] (1988)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Service Medal]] (1965, 1966, 2006)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.com/bio/award-esm.htm |title=Biography: 2 Exceptional Service Medals |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[NASA Outstanding Leadership Medal]] (1992)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Space Flight Medal]] (1981, 1983)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n\n==Awards and honors==\n[[File:20-02-001-aviation.jpg|thumb|right|Plaque of Young at the [[Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame]]]]\n\n* Inducted into six Aviation and Astronaut Halls of Fame<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* General [[James E. Hill]] Lifetime Space Achievement Award<ref>{{cite web |url=http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/node/580.html |title=The General James E. Hill Lifetime Space Achievement Award |publisher=National Space Symposium |date=2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615164321/http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/node/580.html |archivedate=June 15, 2013 }}</ref> from the [[Space Foundation]] (2010)<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/media/press-releases/legendary-astronaut-john-young-to-receive-general-james-e-hill-lifetime-space-a.html |title=Legendary Astronaut John Young to Receive General James E. Hill Lifetime Space Achievement Award |publisher=National Space Symposium |first=Janet |last=Stevens |date=January 22, 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615164322/http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/media/press-releases/legendary-astronaut-john-young-to-receive-general-james-e-hill-lifetime-space-a.html |archivedate=June 15, 2013 }}</ref>\n* Exceptional Engineering Achievement Award (1985)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Academy of Achievement|Golden Plate Award]] for Science and Exploration (1993)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.achievement.org/our-history/golden-plate-awards/all-honorees/ |title=Golden Plate Awardees listed by year |publisher=Academy of Achievement |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[American Astronautical Society]] Space Flight Award (1993)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n*In 1995, Young was inducted into the [[International Air & Space Hall of Fame]] at the [[San Diego Air & Space Museum]].<ref>Sprekelmeyer, Linda, editor. ''These We Honor: The International Aerospace Hall of Fame''. Donning Co. Publishers, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-57864-397-4}}.</ref>\n*In 2001, Young was inducted into the [[Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Captain John W. Young |url=http://www.gaaviationhalloffame.com/Hall-of-Fame.48.0.html?avid=93 |access-date=October 9, 2018 |website=Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame}}</ref>\n* NASA Ambassador of Exploration (2005)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/centers/johnson/news/releases/H05-192.html |title=NASA Names Astronaut John Young Ambassador of Exploration |publisher=NASA |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* He was the first John Young History Maker Honoree in 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cflhistory.org/cflhistory.org/wp-content/uploads/2017-John-Young-History-Maker-Sponsorship-Package.pdf |title=11th Annual John Young History Maker Celebration |publisher=Historical Society of Central Florida |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* Six [[Honorary degree|honorary]] doctorate degrees<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Florida State Road 423|John Young Parkway]], a major highway in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] and [[Kissimmee, Florida]], is named for him. When he heard the highway was named for him, he said \"Them boys shouldn't a'done that. I ain't dead yet\".<ref name=\"sts61\" /> An elementary school ([[Orange County Public Schools|OCPS]]) on the parkway also bears his name.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://johnyounges.ocps.net/ |title=John Young Elementary School Homepage |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=John Young Elementary School}}</ref>\n* The planetarium at the [[Orlando Science Center]] was originally named in his honor.<ref name=\"orsent19901028\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1990-10-28/news/9010240091_1_telescope-science-center-planets |title=Where Stargazers Can Get The Big Picture |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |first=Cindy |last=Schreuder |date=October 28, 1990 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n*Ranked as the No. 3 most-popular space hero in a 2010 [[Space Foundation]] survey<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.spacefoundation.org/news/space-foundation-survey-reveals-broad-range-space-heroes-early-astronauts-still-most |title=Space Foundation Survey Reveals Broad Range of Space Heroes; Early Astronauts Still the Most Inspirational |publisher=Space Foundation |first=Carol |last=Hively |date=October 27, 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107174826/https://www.spacefoundation.org/news/space-foundation-survey-reveals-broad-range-space-heroes-early-astronauts-still-most |archive-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Recipient of ''[[Aviation Week]]''{{'}}s 1998 [[Philip J. Klass]] Award for Lifetime Achievement<ref>{{cite web |url=https://laureates.aviationweek.com/en/winners/previous-winners.html |title=Aviation Week's Laureate Awards Past Winners |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=Aviation Week}}</ref>\n* Asteroid [[5362 Johnyoung]] was named in his memory in 2018\n\nAlong with nine other Gemini astronauts, Young was inducted into the [[International Space Hall of Fame]] in 1982.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28841417/albuquerque_journal/ |title=Astronauts Laud Gemini as Precursor to Shuttle |last1=Shay |first1=Erin |newspaper=Albuquerque Journal |location=Albuquerque, New Mexico |date=October 3, 1982 |page=3 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Young, along with the other 12 Gemini astronauts, was inducted into the second [[U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame]] class in 1993.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33582881/florida_today/ |title=Activities Honor Gemini Astronauts |newspaper=Florida Today |location=Cocoa, Florida |date=March 14, 1993 |page=41 |via=Newspapers.com |last1=Clark |first1=Amy}}</ref>\n\n===Organizations===\n* [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]] [[fellow]]<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.com/bio/org.htm |title=Biography: Organization Memberships |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* American Astronautical Society fellow<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\" /><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]] fellow<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\" /><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Tau Beta Pi]] Engineering Honor Society member<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tbp.org/about/Dist/Astronauts.cfm |title=Astronauts and Scientists |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=Tau Beta Pi}}</ref>\n* [[Sigma Gamma Tau]] Aerospace Engineering Honor Society member<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* Georgia Tech [[ANAK Society]] member<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kp5sCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=georgia+tech+anak+society+john+young&source=bl&ots=xmFrxa_pFd&sig=iqN7YnTgt_4jKESg5JfKT9eC0RQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjji5297cTYAhWGvVMKHXLKDCkQ6AEIPzAD#v=onepage&q=georgia%20tech%20anak%20society%20john%20young&f=false |title=Secret Societies Vol. 3: The Collegiate Secret Societies of America |last1=Francis |first1=Arthur Morius |page=26 |chapter=2 |publisher=Lulu.com |date=February 20, 2015 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}{{self-published source}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n* [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity member<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sigmachi.org/the-sigma-chi-museum |publisher=Sigma Chi Fraternity |title=The Sigma Chi Museum |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, [[Northrop Grumman]] announced that the [[Cygnus spacecraft]] for their tenth cargo resupply mission to the [[International Space Station]] would be named S.S. ''John Young''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.space.com/42250-cygnus-cargo-ship-apollo-john-young.html |title=Space Station-Bound Cargo Ship Named for Moonwalker John Young |work=Space.com |last=Pearlman |first=Robert Z. |date=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Florida State Road 423]] is named in his honor, as is [[Orange County Public Schools|John Young Elementary School]] in Orlando, Florida.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volz |first1=Brianna |title=Astronaut John Young, who grew up in Orlando, dies at 87 |url=https://www.clickorlando.com/news/space-news/astronaut-john-young-dies-at-87 |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |work=WKMG |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Scott Kelly (astronaut) | Scott Kelly]] (an American astronaut who [[ISS year long mission | spent nearly a year aboard the International Space Station]]) had high praise for Young in his memoir, ''[[Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery]]''. Upon learning that Young would interview him as part of his astronaut selection process, Kelly listed some of Young's more impressive achievements, and then stated simply, \"He was what you might call an astronaut's astronaut, a living legend. I wanted to be just like him.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Kelly |first=Scott |others=With Margaret Lazarus Dean |title=Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery |title-link=Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf, a division of Penguin Random House |year=2017 |page=201 |isbn=9781524731595}}</ref>\n\n==In media==\nIn the 1995 film ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]'', Young was played by Ben Marley.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0112384/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=Apollo 13, Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> In the 1998 [[HBO]] [[miniseries]], ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'', he was played by [[John Posey (actor)|John Posey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120570/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=From the Earth to the Moon, Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYoung is one of the astronauts featured in the 2007 documentary film and book ''[[In the Shadow of the Moon (2007 film)|In the Shadow of the Moon]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0925248/fullcredits#cast |title=In the Shadow of the Moon: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> the 2007 documentary film ''[[The Wonder of It All (2007 film)|The Wonder of It All]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0928406/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=The Wonder of It All: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> and the 2008 Discovery Channel series ''[[When We Left Earth: The NASA Missions|When We Left Earth]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1233514/fullcredits |title=When We Left Earth: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung's voice during the STS-1 mission can be heard in the song \"[[Countdown (Rush song)|Countdown]]\" by [[Rush (band)|Rush]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Spaceflight}}\n*[[List of spaceflight records]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Neal |authorlink=Neal Thompson |title=Light This Candle: The Life & Times of Alan Shepard, America's First Spaceman |edition=1st |date=2004 |publisher=Crown Publishers |location=New York |isbn=0-609-61001-5 |oclc=52631310 |lccn=2003015688 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lightthiscandlel00thom }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Conversation-With-John-Young-1563092.php \"Conversation With John Young\"], ''Houston Chronicle'' (December 17, 2004)\n*[http://www.balettie.com/young/ \"The Big Picture: Ways to Mitigate or Prevent Very Bad Planet Earth Events\"], an essay by Young\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{C-SPAN|johnyoung04}}\n*{{IMDb name|0974135}}\n*{{Find a Grave|186428895}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Alan Shepard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief of the Astronaut Office]]\n|years=1974\u20131987}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Daniel Brandenstein]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{People who have traveled to the Moon}}\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 2}}\n{{Gemini program}}\n{{Congressional Space Medal of Honor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, John}}\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:John Young| ]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:1965 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1966 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1969 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1972 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1981 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1983 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Apollo 10]]\n[[Category:Apollo 16]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:Aviators from California]]\n[[Category:Apollo program astronauts]]\n[[Category:People who have walked on the Moon]]\n[[Category:American aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:United States Navy astronauts]]\n[[Category:NASA civilian astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Astronaut Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Test Pilot School alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n[[Category:National Aviation Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:American test pilots]]\n[[Category:NASA people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Congressional Space Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Exceptional Achievement Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Exceptional Service Medal]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Toastmasters members]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Florida]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Orlando, Florida]]\n[[Category:Project Gemini astronauts